up until 9.

15
00:00:48,920 --> 00:00:51,920
So all good on that point?

16
00:00:51,920 --> 00:00:54,040
Cool.

17
00:00:54,040 --> 00:00:54,960
Great.

18
00:00:54,960 --> 00:00:58,520
So with that, we're going
to start the lecture.

19
00:00:58,520 --> 00:01:03,510
So today, we're going to
talk about LLM tuning.

20
00:01:03,510 --> 00:01:08,750
So as usual, we're just going
to recap what we saw last time.

21
00:01:08,750 --> 00:01:11,990
So last time was
already two weeks ago.

22
00:01:11,990 --> 00:01:15,670
But we talked about
how to train an LLM.

23
00:01:15,670 --> 00:01:21,430
And in particular, we've
looked at two important steps.

24
00:01:21,430 --> 00:01:24,790
So the first one was
called pre-training,

25
00:01:24,790 --> 00:01:29,750
where you're basically taking a
model that has been initialized,

26
00:01:29,750 --> 00:01:33,990
and you're trying to teach
the model about language,

27
00:01:33,990 --> 00:01:35,750
about code.

28
00:01:35,750 --> 00:01:38,190
So you have this step
that is very time

29
00:01:38,190 --> 00:01:42,710
consuming, expensive,
compute heavy, that

30
00:01:42,710 --> 00:01:44,950
is happening on a lot of data.

31
00:01:44,950 --> 00:01:48,030
So we've seen
training optimizations

32
00:01:48,030 --> 00:01:50,150
on how to make that happen.

33
00:01:50,150 --> 00:01:54,610
So we've seen techniques to
parallelize that across GPUs.

34
00:01:54,610 --> 00:02:00,140
So we've seen data parallelism
methods and, in particular, 0.

35
00:02:00,140 --> 00:02:03,180
So the variant 0, 1, 2, 3.

36
00:02:03,180 --> 00:02:06,740
And we've also seen very quickly
what model parallelism was

37
00:02:06,740 --> 00:02:08,500
in this case.

38
00:02:08,500 --> 00:02:11,460
So at the end of
this step, what you

39
00:02:11,460 --> 00:02:16,440
obtain is a model that knows
about the structure of language,

40
00:02:16,440 --> 00:02:17,580
about codes--

41
00:02:17,580 --> 00:02:20,620
basically, all the texts
that it has been fed.

42
00:02:20,620 --> 00:02:26,780
But what this model can do is
only predict the next token.

43
00:02:26,780 --> 00:02:31,820
So it's a great autocompleter,
but it's not a helpful model

44
00:02:31,820 --> 00:02:35,700
yet, which is why we
have a second step.

45
00:02:35,700 --> 00:02:40,420
And we saw here, it's typically
called finetuning or SFT

46
00:02:40,420 --> 00:02:42,860
for Supervised Fine Tuning.

47
00:02:42,860 --> 00:02:47,780
So here what we do is we
take our pre-trained model,

48
00:02:47,780 --> 00:02:50,620
and we train it
for specific tasks.

49
00:02:50,620 --> 00:02:55,260
So nowadays, you have ChatGPT
and all these chat assistants.

50
00:02:55,260 --> 00:02:58,110
So this can be one application.

51
00:02:58,110 --> 00:03:01,290
So transforming your
model into an assistant.

52
00:03:01,290 --> 00:03:07,010
And so here, the goal is to
teach the model how to behave.

53
00:03:07,010 --> 00:03:09,570
So the model already
knows what language

54
00:03:09,570 --> 00:03:12,530
is, what code is, et cetera.

55
00:03:12,530 --> 00:03:17,170
And you're just trying to make
it behave like the use case

56
00:03:17,170 --> 00:03:19,930
that you're trying
to tune it for.

57
00:03:19,930 --> 00:03:22,330
So typically here,
what you have is

58
00:03:22,330 --> 00:03:25,450
a data set that is
much smaller in scale,

59
00:03:25,450 --> 00:03:28,570
but of much higher quality.

60
00:03:28,570 --> 00:03:33,370
And you're basically taking your
model, your pre-trained model,

61
00:03:33,370 --> 00:03:37,370
and teaching it
exactly which tokens

62
00:03:37,370 --> 00:03:41,930
to predict with the next
token prediction task.

63
00:03:41,930 --> 00:03:48,330
And we've seen, LoRA, which is
a parameter efficient method,

64
00:03:48,330 --> 00:03:53,080
which does not tune all the
weights, but in a clever way,

65
00:03:53,080 --> 00:03:56,720
introduces low rank
matrices that are

66
00:03:56,720 --> 00:03:59,760
the ones that are being tuned.

67
00:03:59,760 --> 00:04:02,000
And we had stopped there.

68
00:04:02,000 --> 00:04:05,320
So what we're going
to see today is

69
00:04:05,320 --> 00:04:09,520
how to align the model to
align with, what we call,

70
00:04:09,520 --> 00:04:11,640
human preferences.

71
00:04:11,640 --> 00:04:13,360
And so here, we're
taking our model

72
00:04:13,360 --> 00:04:16,120
that has been finetuned
for a specific task.

73
00:04:16,120 --> 00:04:21,040
And trying to align
our model to make

74
00:04:21,040 --> 00:04:23,380
it more something that
a human would like

75
00:04:23,380 --> 00:04:27,080
or that some metric
that we're defining

76
00:04:27,080 --> 00:04:29,960
would be more aligned with that.

77
00:04:29,960 --> 00:04:33,120
So as an example, let's suppose
if you have an assistant

78
00:04:33,120 --> 00:04:35,880
at the end step 2.

79
00:04:35,880 --> 00:04:38,240
So it's very much possible
that your assistant

80
00:04:38,240 --> 00:04:43,640
is behaving the way you want,
but not, let's say, at the tone

81
00:04:43,640 --> 00:04:44,260
that you want.

82
00:04:44,260 --> 00:04:48,940
So it's not, let's say,
friendly or it's not safe.

83
00:04:48,940 --> 00:04:53,260
So you want to tune those
aspects in that third step.

84
00:04:56,270 --> 00:04:57,250
Cool.

85
00:04:57,250 --> 00:05:01,670
So this step is called
preference tuning.

86
00:05:01,670 --> 00:05:04,630
And we're going to
exactly see what that is.

87
00:05:04,630 --> 00:05:07,270
So here for context,
let's suppose

88
00:05:07,270 --> 00:05:09,990
that we have an SFT model.

89
00:05:09,990 --> 00:05:12,230
And so by SFT model,
I mean a model

90
00:05:12,230 --> 00:05:14,870
that has gone through
the pre-trained stage

91
00:05:14,870 --> 00:05:17,310
and the finetuning stage.

92
00:05:17,310 --> 00:05:20,110
And so for instance,
we may ask our model

93
00:05:20,110 --> 00:05:23,590
to suggest a new activity we
could do with our teddy bear.

94
00:05:23,590 --> 00:05:26,710
And here the model,
let's say, responds with,

95
00:05:26,710 --> 00:05:30,030
"I would suggest you to not
spend much time with your teddy

96
00:05:30,030 --> 00:05:31,310
bear at all."

97
00:05:31,310 --> 00:05:34,450
So this is the response
of an assistant,

98
00:05:34,450 --> 00:05:38,510
but it's not necessarily
aligned with what we want.

99
00:05:38,510 --> 00:05:43,430
So the idea here is to
take these, quote unquote,

100
00:05:43,430 --> 00:05:50,500
"bad outputs" and find an output
or rewrite an output that we

101
00:05:50,500 --> 00:05:53,980
would want to have instead.

102
00:05:53,980 --> 00:06:00,260
So this pair would be what
we call a preference pair.

103
00:06:00,260 --> 00:06:05,740
So in other words, given this
prompt, we have two responses--

104
00:06:05,740 --> 00:06:08,640
one that we want to
see, which is this one.

105
00:06:08,640 --> 00:06:10,540
And I'm going to
read it in a second.

106
00:06:10,540 --> 00:06:13,580
And then the other one
that we do not want to see.

107
00:06:13,580 --> 00:06:15,760
So for instance,
in this example,

108
00:06:15,760 --> 00:06:18,900
the answer we want to
see is, "Of course,

109
00:06:18,900 --> 00:06:21,000
teddy bears not only
make awesome companions

110
00:06:21,000 --> 00:06:24,780
for a delightful sleep, but can
also be great buddies for fun

111
00:06:24,780 --> 00:06:29,700
activities," and just like
suggest some activities.

112
00:06:29,700 --> 00:06:33,060
Does the setup sound good?

113
00:06:33,060 --> 00:06:34,260
Yeah?

114
00:06:34,260 --> 00:06:37,980
So long story short, we
want to align our model

115
00:06:37,980 --> 00:06:41,260
with human preferences.

116
00:06:41,260 --> 00:06:47,700
So you may ask, we have this
finetuning step already.

117
00:06:47,700 --> 00:06:50,930
Why would we want to
have a third step?

118
00:06:50,930 --> 00:06:54,850
Well, during the second step,
which is the finetuning stage,

119
00:06:54,850 --> 00:07:00,570
if you remember, what we did was
construct a very high quality

120
00:07:00,570 --> 00:07:06,530
data set of the kinds of prompts
on which we want our model

121
00:07:06,530 --> 00:07:08,690
to behave in a certain way.

122
00:07:08,690 --> 00:07:11,770
So in order to compose
such a data set,

123
00:07:11,770 --> 00:07:16,090
it's actually something that
is very time consuming and very

124
00:07:16,090 --> 00:07:19,650
actually difficult,
because the data set must

125
00:07:19,650 --> 00:07:21,970
be of very high quality.

126
00:07:21,970 --> 00:07:25,090
And in this case,
what we're doing

127
00:07:25,090 --> 00:07:29,810
is not really teaching the model
exactly what it should generate,

128
00:07:29,810 --> 00:07:34,410
but rather telling the
model what kind of output

129
00:07:34,410 --> 00:07:36,970
it should prefer.

130
00:07:36,970 --> 00:07:41,330
So we're less in
"please generate that"

131
00:07:41,330 --> 00:07:45,810
kind of thing and more
a "I prefer this option"

132
00:07:45,810 --> 00:07:48,200
kind of thing.

133
00:07:48,200 --> 00:07:53,520
And so typically, if we
asked you write a poem,

134
00:07:53,520 --> 00:07:57,040
write a great poem
from scratch, it

135
00:07:57,040 --> 00:08:00,880
would typically be much more
difficult to do rather than just

136
00:08:00,880 --> 00:08:05,840
showing you two poems, one
bad poem and one great poem,

137
00:08:05,840 --> 00:08:11,720
and ask you to just say
which one is better.

138
00:08:11,720 --> 00:08:17,680
So in order to obtain the data
sets, it's already much easier.

139
00:08:17,680 --> 00:08:20,080
The second reason is--

140
00:08:20,080 --> 00:08:24,400
so during the SFT stage,
when we compose our data set

141
00:08:24,400 --> 00:08:27,400
of very high quality,
there is one aspect

142
00:08:27,400 --> 00:08:29,920
that we really try
to get right, which

143
00:08:29,920 --> 00:08:33,600
is the distribution of prompts.

144
00:08:33,600 --> 00:08:38,880
And what I mean by that is if
we have too much of a given

145
00:08:38,880 --> 00:08:43,200
of prompt, our model
will be more biased

146
00:08:43,200 --> 00:08:46,990
towards responding in
that particular way.

147
00:08:46,990 --> 00:08:49,910
So what people
try to do is to be

148
00:08:49,910 --> 00:08:53,510
careful about the
distribution of prompts that

149
00:08:53,510 --> 00:08:56,070
are in the SFT data.

150
00:08:56,070 --> 00:08:59,630
And so here, let's say
if our model misbehaves,

151
00:08:59,630 --> 00:09:03,590
if we were thinking about just
adding one example in the SFT

152
00:09:03,590 --> 00:09:07,790
data set, well, we would have
to be very careful about which

153
00:09:07,790 --> 00:09:10,470
prompt we're adding
and whether it's not

154
00:09:10,470 --> 00:09:15,670
going to bias the model like
too much in that direction.

155
00:09:15,670 --> 00:09:17,470
So that's the second reason.

156
00:09:17,470 --> 00:09:19,710
And then, the third
reason is what

157
00:09:19,710 --> 00:09:23,190
I mentioned, which is
the SFT data is typically

158
00:09:23,190 --> 00:09:24,370
very high quality.

159
00:09:24,370 --> 00:09:28,350
So if you're looking
at all the missteps

160
00:09:28,350 --> 00:09:30,750
that your model is
doing and trying

161
00:09:30,750 --> 00:09:34,660
to put that in the SFT data,
you'll just have a hard time.

162
00:09:34,660 --> 00:09:37,630
It takes a lot of time.

163
00:09:37,630 --> 00:09:44,900
But one note here is if your
SFT data is misbehaving a lot,

164
00:09:44,900 --> 00:09:48,320
it may also be due to the
fact that your SFT data

165
00:09:48,320 --> 00:09:51,580
set has some problem.

166
00:09:51,580 --> 00:09:54,540
So preference tuning is not
the answer to everything.

167
00:09:54,540 --> 00:09:59,140
Maybe it's better sometimes to
just check your SFT data set

168
00:09:59,140 --> 00:10:02,696
for some issues.

169
00:10:02,696 --> 00:10:03,640
Does that sound good?

170
00:10:03,640 --> 00:10:04,140
Yeah.

171
00:10:04,140 --> 00:10:07,598
[AUDIO OUT]

172
00:10:20,442 --> 00:10:23,080
Yeah, so to do that in the
preference tuning stage?

173
00:10:23,080 --> 00:10:25,260
OK, so the question
is, we saw LoRA

174
00:10:25,260 --> 00:10:28,260
for SFT, what is the equivalent
for preference tuning?

175
00:10:28,260 --> 00:10:31,260
So we'll see that
later in the lecture.

176
00:10:31,260 --> 00:10:37,980
But you can think of LoRA as
being some way to, I guess,

177
00:10:37,980 --> 00:10:41,130
reduce the number of parameters
that you need to tune.

178
00:10:41,130 --> 00:10:43,810
That is slightly different
with the objective function

179
00:10:43,810 --> 00:10:45,890
that you're using
to train your model.

180
00:10:45,890 --> 00:10:48,690
And here, preference
tuning, you can think of it

181
00:10:48,690 --> 00:10:52,010
more as a different
objective function,

182
00:10:52,010 --> 00:10:53,970
but it may very
well be something

183
00:10:53,970 --> 00:10:56,730
that you also use LoRA for.

184
00:10:56,730 --> 00:10:59,650
So the two are not incompatible.

185
00:10:59,650 --> 00:11:02,650
But it will become
more clear later on.

186
00:11:02,650 --> 00:11:04,690
But yeah, great question.

187
00:11:04,690 --> 00:11:09,370
One last thing I will add
here is another difference

188
00:11:09,370 --> 00:11:14,530
with the SFT stage is that
preference tuning allows us

189
00:11:14,530 --> 00:11:18,842
to inject some negative signal.

190
00:11:18,842 --> 00:11:23,530
Because SFT is all about
teaching the model about what

191
00:11:23,530 --> 00:11:25,810
it should predict,
but it does not

192
00:11:25,810 --> 00:11:30,248
teach the model about what
it should not predict.

193
00:11:30,248 --> 00:11:32,290
And we will see that
preference tuning allows you

194
00:11:32,290 --> 00:11:33,700
to inject some negative signal.

195
00:11:36,610 --> 00:11:37,950
Cool.

196
00:11:37,950 --> 00:11:44,080
So to start, of course, we need
to have our preference pairs.

197
00:11:44,080 --> 00:11:49,160
And so we're going to look at
this data collection step first.

198
00:11:49,160 --> 00:11:51,280
So here's the setup.

199
00:11:51,280 --> 00:11:53,240
You have a prompt.

200
00:11:53,240 --> 00:11:55,440
Let's say write a poem.

201
00:11:55,440 --> 00:11:57,920
And you have a given
response, which

202
00:11:57,920 --> 00:12:02,280
is the poem that is being
generated by the model.

203
00:12:02,280 --> 00:12:08,160
You have a few ways to
construct your preference data.

204
00:12:08,160 --> 00:12:14,120
So either you start with
a pointwise mindset,

205
00:12:14,120 --> 00:12:18,000
where you score
each proposed poem

206
00:12:18,000 --> 00:12:19,960
with some kind of
pointwise score,

207
00:12:19,960 --> 00:12:23,960
and here pointwise
score means a score

208
00:12:23,960 --> 00:12:28,000
just relative to
one observation.

209
00:12:28,000 --> 00:12:32,480
You could very well do that, but
I will say it's kind of hard.

210
00:12:32,480 --> 00:12:34,820
It's kind of tough as
a human to say, OK,

211
00:12:34,820 --> 00:12:36,860
this one is, I
don't know, a 0.9.

212
00:12:36,860 --> 00:12:38,430
This one is like a 0.2.

213
00:12:38,430 --> 00:12:44,110
It's not super clear exactly
how you would scale that.

214
00:12:44,110 --> 00:12:50,630
The second idea is for you to
get two observations at the time

215
00:12:50,630 --> 00:12:53,910
and for you to say
which one is better.

216
00:12:53,910 --> 00:12:58,270
So this one is called
pairwise preference data.

217
00:12:58,270 --> 00:13:01,990
And it's much easier.

218
00:13:01,990 --> 00:13:04,630
And then, the third
one is listwise,

219
00:13:04,630 --> 00:13:09,510
which is get a list
of, let's say, n poems,

220
00:13:09,510 --> 00:13:12,470
and then you just rank
which one is best, which one

221
00:13:12,470 --> 00:13:15,590
is worst, et cetera, et cetera.

222
00:13:15,590 --> 00:13:18,870
And I guess this one is
easier than pointwise,

223
00:13:18,870 --> 00:13:21,530
because you don't have
to specify, I guess,

224
00:13:21,530 --> 00:13:23,950
how much better it is,
but I guess it's still

225
00:13:23,950 --> 00:13:27,310
a bit more complicated.

226
00:13:27,310 --> 00:13:32,590
And that's the reason why
people typically use pairwise.

227
00:13:32,590 --> 00:13:37,500
So what they do is they collect
pairwise preference data.

228
00:13:37,500 --> 00:13:42,220
Meaning for each prompt, they
have two possible answers,

229
00:13:42,220 --> 00:13:47,540
and then they just specify
which one is better.

230
00:13:47,540 --> 00:13:53,420
And so that's the one we'll
continue this lecture with.

231
00:13:53,420 --> 00:13:58,000
OK, so now you may ask, OK,
great, pairwise preference data.

232
00:13:58,000 --> 00:14:00,100
But how do you get it?

233
00:14:00,100 --> 00:14:02,260
Well, here is the recipe.

234
00:14:02,260 --> 00:14:05,760
So in order to generate
a pair of responses--

235
00:14:05,760 --> 00:14:07,620
so first, you need a prompt.

236
00:14:07,620 --> 00:14:13,660
And we've seen-- previously, I
think it's in lecture probably

237
00:14:13,660 --> 00:14:15,220
3--

238
00:14:15,220 --> 00:14:21,260
that what you could do was
to generate different answers

239
00:14:21,260 --> 00:14:23,900
if you have a temperature
that's positive.

240
00:14:23,900 --> 00:14:27,520
So typically, what people
do is they put this prompt,

241
00:14:27,520 --> 00:14:32,540
let's say, twice into the model
with a positive temperature,

242
00:14:32,540 --> 00:14:34,420
and then they can get
two different answers.

243
00:14:37,050 --> 00:14:39,450
The prompt is
typically something

244
00:14:39,450 --> 00:14:43,170
where we wanted to follow
the distribution of what

245
00:14:43,170 --> 00:14:45,410
the users typically ask.

246
00:14:45,410 --> 00:14:49,450
So the prompt x can be something
that we obtain from the logs

247
00:14:49,450 --> 00:14:54,330
or from, let's say, a
desired set of prompts.

248
00:14:54,330 --> 00:14:58,890
And then what we do is we
have these two observations.

249
00:14:58,890 --> 00:15:03,370
So the first one is the
prompt and the first response.

250
00:15:03,370 --> 00:15:07,490
The second one is the prompt
and the second response.

251
00:15:07,490 --> 00:15:10,130
And what we do is we rate--

252
00:15:10,130 --> 00:15:12,810
we compare them.

253
00:15:12,810 --> 00:15:18,690
So we can compare them with,
of course, human ratings.

254
00:15:18,690 --> 00:15:22,810
But we can also compare them
with some other metrics.

255
00:15:22,810 --> 00:15:25,490
So I'll just list a few.

256
00:15:25,490 --> 00:15:30,076
So we have LLM as a judge,
which you may have heard of,

257
00:15:30,076 --> 00:15:33,000
which we have not
seen yet, which

258
00:15:33,000 --> 00:15:37,480
we will see in a few lectures
that is also typically used

259
00:15:37,480 --> 00:15:44,120
to just compare, I guess, how
much better one observation is

260
00:15:44,120 --> 00:15:46,400
compared to another.

261
00:15:46,400 --> 00:15:50,360
We can also use some other
metrics, rule-based one

262
00:15:50,360 --> 00:15:52,840
like BLEU, ROUGE, et
cetera, although, it

263
00:15:52,840 --> 00:15:56,080
is not as used these days.

264
00:15:56,080 --> 00:16:00,240
And the simplest way to compare
these two observations is

265
00:16:00,240 --> 00:16:04,720
to have a binary
setting, where you say,

266
00:16:04,720 --> 00:16:09,160
OK, is response 1 better
or worse than response 2?

267
00:16:09,160 --> 00:16:14,080
But you could also think
of a more nuanced scale,

268
00:16:14,080 --> 00:16:16,040
meaning you can also
say, OK, response

269
00:16:16,040 --> 00:16:21,760
1 is much better, better,
slightly better, slightly

270
00:16:21,760 --> 00:16:24,280
worse, worse, or much worse.

271
00:16:24,280 --> 00:16:27,360
So this is also something
that you can do.

272
00:16:27,360 --> 00:16:30,350
But there are some challenges
with that approach.

273
00:16:30,350 --> 00:16:33,230
Because for instance,
if you, I don't know,

274
00:16:33,230 --> 00:16:35,630
consider human
ratings, a lot of tasks

275
00:16:35,630 --> 00:16:38,070
are a little bit subjective.

276
00:16:38,070 --> 00:16:41,230
So in a lot of cases,
actually, what people do

277
00:16:41,230 --> 00:16:48,710
is having a pairwise preference
data set on the binary scale.

278
00:16:48,710 --> 00:16:51,460
So only is it better or worse.

279
00:16:54,350 --> 00:16:57,030
Does that sound good?

280
00:16:57,030 --> 00:16:58,510
Yeah.

281
00:16:58,510 --> 00:17:04,069
OK, so another way to obtain
that data is to have--

282
00:17:04,069 --> 00:17:07,990
to find in your logs a
response that you did not

283
00:17:07,990 --> 00:17:13,790
like to take that response
and to rewrite it,

284
00:17:13,790 --> 00:17:16,349
which is basically
what we did here.

285
00:17:16,349 --> 00:17:20,310
So here, when we have the
response here, what we did

286
00:17:20,310 --> 00:17:27,069
is take the response
and rewrite a good one.

287
00:17:27,069 --> 00:17:28,920
So this is also what people do.

288
00:17:28,920 --> 00:17:30,700
But of course, it is
a bit more involved,

289
00:17:30,700 --> 00:17:32,520
because you need to generate.

290
00:17:32,520 --> 00:17:36,860
And I told you that generation
was kind of costly and tough,

291
00:17:36,860 --> 00:17:38,190
but this is also possible.

292
00:17:41,740 --> 00:17:43,510
Does the data
collection make sense?

293
00:17:46,820 --> 00:17:47,900
Yeah?

294
00:17:47,900 --> 00:17:48,780
Cool.

295
00:17:48,780 --> 00:17:53,940
OK, so now, we have
our preference data.

296
00:17:53,940 --> 00:18:00,860
And what we want is to align our
model to prefer responses that

297
00:18:00,860 --> 00:18:04,820
were preferred by the
rating, and, I guess,

298
00:18:04,820 --> 00:18:08,740
down weight the responses
that were not preferred.

299
00:18:08,740 --> 00:18:11,540
And so in order to
do that, we will see

300
00:18:11,540 --> 00:18:14,203
a method that's called RLHF.

301
00:18:14,203 --> 00:18:16,620
RLHF.

302
00:18:16,620 --> 00:18:22,380
And I'll see-- we'll see that
in more details in a second.

303
00:18:22,380 --> 00:18:28,970
But as the name indicates,
RLHF relies on RL.

304
00:18:28,970 --> 00:18:32,530
So I'm just going to
start with some RL basics.

305
00:18:32,530 --> 00:18:34,550
So do we have any
RL experts here?

306
00:18:37,170 --> 00:18:38,170
Yeah?

307
00:18:38,170 --> 00:18:38,670
No?

308
00:18:38,670 --> 00:18:41,070
[CHUCKLES] So no need
to be an RL expert.

309
00:18:41,070 --> 00:18:42,070
So don't worry.

310
00:18:42,070 --> 00:18:45,010
We'll go really slowly on that.

311
00:18:45,010 --> 00:18:51,770
So in the RL world, what people
do is they have an agent--

312
00:18:51,770 --> 00:18:54,610
and here, I mean the
agent in RL term--

313
00:18:54,610 --> 00:18:58,490
which interacts
with an environment.

314
00:18:58,490 --> 00:19:00,170
So what does it do?

315
00:19:00,170 --> 00:19:05,010
It is at a given state,
at, let's say, time t,

316
00:19:05,010 --> 00:19:09,290
it can take an action at time t.

317
00:19:09,290 --> 00:19:14,850
And it takes that action
according to some policy.

318
00:19:14,850 --> 00:19:19,530
The policy is typically
denoted pi, pi of theta

319
00:19:19,530 --> 00:19:22,490
of the action given the state.

320
00:19:22,490 --> 00:19:27,520
So what that policy
means is simply

321
00:19:27,520 --> 00:19:30,480
giving you the
probability of you

322
00:19:30,480 --> 00:19:35,080
taking an action given a state.

323
00:19:35,080 --> 00:19:36,800
Easy, right?

324
00:19:36,800 --> 00:19:42,960
And so given that the
agent takes some action,

325
00:19:42,960 --> 00:19:46,880
it also receives some rewards.

326
00:19:46,880 --> 00:19:48,740
So sometimes, it's
a good reward.

327
00:19:48,740 --> 00:19:50,070
Sometimes, it's bad rewards.

328
00:19:52,720 --> 00:19:55,680
So what we're going
to do is to leverage

329
00:19:55,680 --> 00:20:01,880
that mindset for our
preference tuning exercise.

330
00:20:01,880 --> 00:20:06,640
So let's see together how we
can transpose these quantities

331
00:20:06,640 --> 00:20:09,240
in the LLM world.

332
00:20:09,240 --> 00:20:12,560
So what is the agent?

333
00:20:12,560 --> 00:20:15,520
The agent is the LLM.

334
00:20:15,520 --> 00:20:20,160
So in terms of the
state that it is in,

335
00:20:20,160 --> 00:20:25,350
so it's simply the input
that it has so far.

336
00:20:25,350 --> 00:20:30,110
So the action that it wants to
do is to predict the next token.

337
00:20:30,110 --> 00:20:32,650
So it basically
always wonders, OK,

338
00:20:32,650 --> 00:20:36,750
what is the next token
given this input?

339
00:20:36,750 --> 00:20:39,830
And this action
or this next token

340
00:20:39,830 --> 00:20:44,310
is among the set of
tokens that are out there.

341
00:20:44,310 --> 00:20:45,270
So if you want--

342
00:20:45,270 --> 00:20:50,350
the environment can be the set
of tokens of your vocabulary.

343
00:20:50,350 --> 00:20:56,270
And in order to decide which
token should come next,

344
00:20:56,270 --> 00:21:02,030
the LLM determines that using
the probability of next token,

345
00:21:02,030 --> 00:21:05,770
which is obtained by when
you do your forward pass,

346
00:21:05,770 --> 00:21:08,750
and when you look at the
probability distribution

347
00:21:08,750 --> 00:21:15,430
as an output, which is
basically our policy.

348
00:21:15,430 --> 00:21:20,110
So our policy here is
simply equal to the output

349
00:21:20,110 --> 00:21:24,140
of the LLM given
the input in order

350
00:21:24,140 --> 00:21:27,700
to determine the next token.

351
00:21:27,700 --> 00:21:29,620
So far, so good?

352
00:21:29,620 --> 00:21:32,860
And now, we're adding
one additional thing.

353
00:21:32,860 --> 00:21:37,460
So I told you we're composing
our preference data sets.

354
00:21:37,460 --> 00:21:44,660
And we want to know which output
is better than the other output.

355
00:21:44,660 --> 00:21:47,500
And so we're going to
use that for our reward.

356
00:21:47,500 --> 00:21:49,960
We're going to somehow
use that for our reward.

357
00:21:49,960 --> 00:21:51,530
And we'll see how
we will use that.

358
00:21:54,860 --> 00:21:56,880
So I'm going to just
recap that part.

359
00:21:56,880 --> 00:22:00,500
So we have our LLM
take some input,

360
00:22:00,500 --> 00:22:03,800
and then it wants to
predict the next token.

361
00:22:03,800 --> 00:22:06,020
It wants to take this action.

362
00:22:06,020 --> 00:22:09,940
So in order to do that, it uses
the probability distribution

363
00:22:09,940 --> 00:22:10,710
that it outputs.

364
00:22:13,260 --> 00:22:16,500
And then, the token
that it predicts

365
00:22:16,500 --> 00:22:19,610
or the output that
it generates then

366
00:22:19,610 --> 00:22:23,690
receives some reward that
is going to feed back

367
00:22:23,690 --> 00:22:26,590
into tuning the agent.

368
00:22:26,590 --> 00:22:27,890
And here is the LLM.

369
00:22:27,890 --> 00:22:28,765
Yep.

370
00:22:28,765 --> 00:22:32,565
[AUDIO OUT]

371
00:22:36,850 --> 00:22:39,010
So the question is,
wouldn't that be expensive

372
00:22:39,010 --> 00:22:40,990
if we do this for all pairs?

373
00:22:40,990 --> 00:22:42,230
Why would that be expensive?

374
00:22:42,230 --> 00:22:45,674
[AUDIO OUT]

375
00:22:53,054 --> 00:22:54,038
Mm-hmm.

376
00:22:54,038 --> 00:22:57,490
[AUDIO OUT]

377
00:22:57,490 --> 00:22:58,090
Yeah, so--

378
00:22:58,090 --> 00:22:59,850
[AUDIO OUT]

379
00:22:59,850 --> 00:23:02,730
Yeah, the question is, what do
you do in terms of how expensive

380
00:23:02,730 --> 00:23:03,230
that is?

381
00:23:03,230 --> 00:23:06,970
So yeah, typically, people
take batches, for instance.

382
00:23:06,970 --> 00:23:08,030
But I would not--

383
00:23:08,030 --> 00:23:09,912
so it is indeed expensive.

384
00:23:09,912 --> 00:23:12,370
But we're going to see a little
bit some order of magnitude

385
00:23:12,370 --> 00:23:13,710
and how that works.

386
00:23:13,710 --> 00:23:18,360
But you can think of this
as being kind of a training

387
00:23:18,360 --> 00:23:22,040
procedure that could be seen as
expensive as some other training

388
00:23:22,040 --> 00:23:22,580
procedure.

389
00:23:22,580 --> 00:23:26,068
There's nothing that
makes this more expensive,

390
00:23:26,068 --> 00:23:27,360
but we're going to see exactly.

391
00:23:27,360 --> 00:23:31,280
So I think there are some points
that you're touching correctly.

392
00:23:31,280 --> 00:23:35,640
There are some parts
that are added compared

393
00:23:35,640 --> 00:23:38,160
to the regular
supervised-- let's say,

394
00:23:38,160 --> 00:23:40,420
supervised fine tuning setting.

395
00:23:40,420 --> 00:23:42,140
And we're going to
see that in a second.

396
00:23:42,140 --> 00:23:45,633
[AUDIO OUT]

397
00:23:55,200 --> 00:23:58,120
So the question is, does
the reward that you're

398
00:23:58,120 --> 00:24:02,560
getting from here, I guess,
powerful enough for the LLM

399
00:24:02,560 --> 00:24:03,440
to change?

400
00:24:03,440 --> 00:24:05,280
Well, you will see
some expressions

401
00:24:05,280 --> 00:24:08,560
on the internet just
characterizing this training

402
00:24:08,560 --> 00:24:13,440
procedure as it's nearly
not as many signals

403
00:24:13,440 --> 00:24:15,660
as what you would get
for SFT, let's say.

404
00:24:15,660 --> 00:24:19,030
But because for SFT,
you're literally

405
00:24:19,030 --> 00:24:23,910
always taking a partial input
and making the LLM learn

406
00:24:23,910 --> 00:24:28,190
how to generate the next token.

407
00:24:28,190 --> 00:24:31,990
But here, you're only
getting roughly one signal

408
00:24:31,990 --> 00:24:33,390
per completion.

409
00:24:33,390 --> 00:24:35,830
So yeah, definitely
it's more sparse.

410
00:24:35,830 --> 00:24:38,670
And that's why you
will see that RLHF

411
00:24:38,670 --> 00:24:43,000
is seen as more an approach
that has sparse signals.

412
00:24:46,830 --> 00:24:47,670
Yeah, yep.

413
00:24:47,670 --> 00:24:50,918
[AUDIO OUT]

414
00:24:53,710 --> 00:24:54,770
Great question.

415
00:24:54,770 --> 00:24:58,052
So the question is, do you
apply a reward for each token

416
00:24:58,052 --> 00:24:59,010
or for the whole thing?

417
00:24:59,010 --> 00:25:00,210
We're going to see
this in more detail,

418
00:25:00,210 --> 00:25:01,568
but it's for the whole thing.

419
00:25:01,568 --> 00:25:02,610
It's for the whole thing.

420
00:25:02,610 --> 00:25:07,010
But we'll see that
in just a second.

421
00:25:07,010 --> 00:25:07,510
Yep.

422
00:25:07,510 --> 00:25:10,772
[AUDIO OUT]

423
00:25:13,110 --> 00:25:14,500
So the AD and--

424
00:25:14,500 --> 00:25:18,260
oh, right, so the question
is, what is the AT and ST.

425
00:25:18,260 --> 00:25:22,940
So just as a reminder, ST
is the state that you're in,

426
00:25:22,940 --> 00:25:26,060
and AT is the action
you want to take.

427
00:25:26,060 --> 00:25:32,020
So in the context of an LLM, the
state that you're in for an LLM

428
00:25:32,020 --> 00:25:35,620
is the input that
you have so far.

429
00:25:35,620 --> 00:25:39,020
And then the action is
which token you want

430
00:25:39,020 --> 00:25:41,360
to generate given that input.

431
00:25:41,360 --> 00:25:41,860
Yep.

432
00:25:44,380 --> 00:25:45,000
Cool.

433
00:25:45,000 --> 00:25:47,820
Yeah, so far so good?

434
00:25:47,820 --> 00:25:49,500
OK, perfect.

435
00:25:49,500 --> 00:25:54,140
So now that we know a little
bit what a mental model could

436
00:25:54,140 --> 00:25:58,580
be for, I guess,
LLM-based RL, I just

437
00:25:58,580 --> 00:26:03,380
want to highlight once more that
what we're trying to achieve

438
00:26:03,380 --> 00:26:13,410
is learn how to align
this policy with rewards.

439
00:26:13,410 --> 00:26:15,690
So we want to learn
theta, and theta

440
00:26:15,690 --> 00:26:21,930
is the parameters of our LLM,
such that pi of theta aligns

441
00:26:21,930 --> 00:26:25,290
with preferences.

442
00:26:25,290 --> 00:26:28,970
And that's where
RLHF comes into play.

443
00:26:28,970 --> 00:26:35,250
So RLHF stands for Reinforcement
Learning from Human Feedback.

444
00:26:35,250 --> 00:26:38,770
And it is typically
composed of two stages.

445
00:26:38,770 --> 00:26:44,530
So the first stage
is you figuring out

446
00:26:44,530 --> 00:26:50,250
how to distinguish good
output from bad output.

447
00:26:50,250 --> 00:26:54,530
So here, all the preference
pairs that you collected

448
00:26:54,530 --> 00:26:59,050
are actually used for you to
learn what is good, what is bad.

449
00:26:59,050 --> 00:27:01,970
So the input here
is the concatenation

450
00:27:01,970 --> 00:27:04,210
of the prompt and the response.

451
00:27:04,210 --> 00:27:07,650
And the output is a score.

452
00:27:07,650 --> 00:27:11,640
So what you want to know given
a prompt and the response, how

453
00:27:11,640 --> 00:27:14,440
good that is.

454
00:27:14,440 --> 00:27:18,200
And then the second step is
the RL step, the Reinforcement

455
00:27:18,200 --> 00:27:19,160
Learning step.

456
00:27:19,160 --> 00:27:24,960
And this is where you use the
rewards to align your model

457
00:27:24,960 --> 00:27:26,560
with the preferences.

458
00:27:26,560 --> 00:27:28,800
So here as input,
you have the prompts.

459
00:27:28,800 --> 00:27:31,520
And what you somehow
want to do is

460
00:27:31,520 --> 00:27:35,480
to be able to generate
y hat that is more

461
00:27:35,480 --> 00:27:38,280
aligned with the rewards.

462
00:27:38,280 --> 00:27:40,980
And by the way, I just
want to call out one thing.

463
00:27:40,980 --> 00:27:46,080
So RLHF is Reinforcement
Learning from Human Feedback.

464
00:27:46,080 --> 00:27:52,080
The Human Feedback part
refers to the labels on which

465
00:27:52,080 --> 00:27:55,040
the reward model is trained.

466
00:27:55,040 --> 00:28:00,760
So if there are preference pairs
are based on human ratings,

467
00:28:00,760 --> 00:28:06,920
then we're relying on human
preferences, then we're in RLHF.

468
00:28:06,920 --> 00:28:10,310
Because you will see out there,
there is also RL, let's say,

469
00:28:10,310 --> 00:28:13,750
AIF, a Reinforcement
Learning from AI Feedback.

470
00:28:13,750 --> 00:28:18,270
And that one is relying
on non-human preferences.

471
00:28:18,270 --> 00:28:21,350
So yeah.

472
00:28:21,350 --> 00:28:22,350
Cool.

473
00:28:22,350 --> 00:28:25,830
OK, so now that we know
what RLHF is and we

474
00:28:25,830 --> 00:28:29,950
know that there are two steps,
we'll go through the first step

475
00:28:29,950 --> 00:28:31,190
naturally.

476
00:28:31,190 --> 00:28:34,030
So here the idea is
we want to construct

477
00:28:34,030 --> 00:28:41,750
a model that knows which output
is good, which output is bad.

478
00:28:41,750 --> 00:28:43,990
And of course,
here, what we want

479
00:28:43,990 --> 00:28:48,510
is to not only consider the
output, but also the input,

480
00:28:48,510 --> 00:28:53,550
because you need to somehow
contextualize that answer.

481
00:28:53,550 --> 00:28:57,070
So let's go with our
favorite example.

482
00:28:57,070 --> 00:28:59,670
So let's suppose you have
the following prompt.

483
00:28:59,670 --> 00:29:04,350
Suggest a new activity I
could do with my teddy bear.

484
00:29:04,350 --> 00:29:09,380
So what you want is to have a
reward model that-- here, we

485
00:29:09,380 --> 00:29:15,260
note RM, --that tells you that
the answer that we rewrote

486
00:29:15,260 --> 00:29:18,540
into the good answer is good.

487
00:29:18,540 --> 00:29:21,300
And we want to somehow have
that model that tells us

488
00:29:21,300 --> 00:29:24,000
that the output that
we constructed--

489
00:29:24,000 --> 00:29:28,660
or that we did not construct,
the output that we saw was bad

490
00:29:28,660 --> 00:29:30,860
is bad.

491
00:29:30,860 --> 00:29:33,300
So we want to somehow
have a model that

492
00:29:33,300 --> 00:29:38,020
takes in the prompts and the
good response and say it's good.

493
00:29:38,020 --> 00:29:41,580
And we want to somehow
have a model that

494
00:29:41,580 --> 00:29:45,460
takes the prompt and the bad
response to say it's bad.

495
00:29:45,460 --> 00:29:50,260
So now the question is, how
do you construct such a model?

496
00:29:50,260 --> 00:29:53,300
Well, in order to
do that, we are

497
00:29:53,300 --> 00:29:55,620
using a formulation
that's called

498
