of a reward model is?

752
00:45:33,140 --> 00:45:35,440
So we're going to
see that a bit later,

753
00:45:35,440 --> 00:45:38,650
but you can think of goods
outputs as being, let's say,

754
00:45:38,650 --> 00:45:42,890
1, bad outputs as
being minus 2, minus 3.

755
00:45:42,890 --> 00:45:47,410
So it's basically on the
continuous scale if you want.

756
00:45:47,410 --> 00:45:50,270
We're going to see an
example in a little bit.

757
00:45:50,270 --> 00:45:51,570
So hopefully, this can--

758
00:45:51,570 --> 00:45:52,890
do you have a question?

759
00:45:52,890 --> 00:45:54,050
Perfect.

760
00:45:54,050 --> 00:45:55,495
We're going to see an example.

761
00:45:55,495 --> 00:45:56,870
So hopefully, that
will be clear.

762
00:45:59,830 --> 00:46:00,330
Cool.

763
00:46:03,510 --> 00:46:07,450
So what we did is
train a reward model.

764
00:46:07,450 --> 00:46:11,410
Now, the second step
is to use that reward

765
00:46:11,410 --> 00:46:17,450
model to align our model,
and by model, I mean the LLM.

766
00:46:17,450 --> 00:46:20,410
The LLM that went through the
pre-training stage and the SFT

767
00:46:20,410 --> 00:46:25,890
stage is the model that we want
to align with human preferences.

768
00:46:25,890 --> 00:46:29,850
We're going to do that using
reinforcement learning.

769
00:46:29,850 --> 00:46:31,970
And we're going to do
that using the reward

770
00:46:31,970 --> 00:46:36,200
model that we just constructed.

771
00:46:36,200 --> 00:46:40,040
So the reward model
here is the model

772
00:46:40,040 --> 00:46:42,400
that we obtained in step one.

773
00:46:42,400 --> 00:46:50,000
And it allows us to distinguish
good outputs and bad outputs.

774
00:46:50,000 --> 00:46:56,640
So here is a general recipe of
how you would align your model.

775
00:46:56,640 --> 00:47:02,680
So first, you would take
your prompt as input.

776
00:47:02,680 --> 00:47:07,320
Your LLM will
generate a completion.

777
00:47:07,320 --> 00:47:13,080
So here, a completion means a
full response from the model.

778
00:47:13,080 --> 00:47:14,560
So by the way,
completion, people

779
00:47:14,560 --> 00:47:17,480
use also the term roll-outs.

780
00:47:17,480 --> 00:47:22,040
So it generates a completion,
a rollout, a full response.

781
00:47:22,040 --> 00:47:25,960
And that full response
along with the prompt

782
00:47:25,960 --> 00:47:29,440
goes into the reward model.

783
00:47:29,440 --> 00:47:31,280
So as we saw, the
reward model right now

784
00:47:31,280 --> 00:47:33,810
knows if it's good, if it's bad.

785
00:47:33,810 --> 00:47:35,870
Let's say, right now, it's bad.

786
00:47:35,870 --> 00:47:39,050
So in practice, it does not
generate the thumbs down.

787
00:47:39,050 --> 00:47:40,450
It generates some kind of score.

788
00:47:40,450 --> 00:47:44,470
So if you want minus
2 let's suppose.

789
00:47:44,470 --> 00:47:49,470
So we take that reward
into consideration.

790
00:47:49,470 --> 00:47:57,710
And then what we do is we tune
the LLM with this information.

791
00:47:57,710 --> 00:47:59,170
So it's more
complicated than that.

792
00:47:59,170 --> 00:48:01,490
And we'll see how we
go about doing this.

793
00:48:01,490 --> 00:48:02,876
But this is the general idea.

794
00:48:05,590 --> 00:48:09,430
So just as a reminder,
the reward model

795
00:48:09,430 --> 00:48:13,030
is the model that we
trained as step one.

796
00:48:13,030 --> 00:48:16,630
And it is a model
that is frozen.

797
00:48:16,630 --> 00:48:18,370
We're not training
the reward model.

798
00:48:18,370 --> 00:48:21,350
The reward model
has been trained.

799
00:48:21,350 --> 00:48:26,150
The model that we're
training is the LLM.

800
00:48:26,150 --> 00:48:31,060
So I think that's an
important point to note.

801
00:48:31,060 --> 00:48:41,940
And our goal is to optimize
for higher rewards but then

802
00:48:41,940 --> 00:48:49,380
without going too far
from the initial model.

803
00:48:49,380 --> 00:48:52,400
So I think the optimizing
for higher rewards,

804
00:48:52,400 --> 00:48:55,860
I think, everyone
agrees with me.

805
00:48:55,860 --> 00:48:58,320
But I just said a
second statement,

806
00:48:58,320 --> 00:49:04,820
which is but we don't want to go
too far from the initial model.

807
00:49:04,820 --> 00:49:06,460
So why would that be?

808
00:49:06,460 --> 00:49:10,510
Why would we want to not deviate
too much from the base model?

809
00:49:10,510 --> 00:49:14,544
[AUDIO OUT]

810
00:49:16,420 --> 00:49:19,315
So one suggested answer is
it will catastrophically

811
00:49:19,315 --> 00:49:20,440
forget what it has learned.

812
00:49:20,440 --> 00:49:21,790
Why would that be a problem?

813
00:49:21,790 --> 00:49:25,564
[AUDIO OUT]

814
00:49:35,310 --> 00:49:35,810
Great.

815
00:49:35,810 --> 00:49:36,370
Yeah.

816
00:49:36,370 --> 00:49:37,828
I think it's a
great way to put it.

817
00:49:37,828 --> 00:49:41,850
So the suggested
answer here is you

818
00:49:41,850 --> 00:49:45,250
have all this knowledge in
your initial model, which

819
00:49:45,250 --> 00:49:48,930
is pre-trained and then
instruction tuned or tuned

820
00:49:48,930 --> 00:49:51,110
and you don't want to
move away too much.

821
00:49:51,110 --> 00:49:52,610
This is exactly it.

822
00:49:52,610 --> 00:49:55,702
So that's one reason.

823
00:49:55,702 --> 00:49:56,910
What could be another reason?

824
00:49:56,910 --> 00:49:57,710
So definitely one.

825
00:49:57,710 --> 00:49:58,710
It's very, very good reason.

826
00:49:58,710 --> 00:49:59,918
What could be another reason?

827
00:50:02,190 --> 00:50:02,690
Yeah.

828
00:50:02,690 --> 00:50:04,870
[AUDIO OUT]

829
00:50:04,870 --> 00:50:05,370
Yep.

830
00:50:05,370 --> 00:50:06,870
So overfitting on that data.

831
00:50:06,870 --> 00:50:07,870
So can you tell me more?

832
00:50:07,870 --> 00:50:11,766
[AUDIO OUT]

833
00:50:14,110 --> 00:50:14,610
Yeah.

834
00:50:14,610 --> 00:50:15,470
Great point.

835
00:50:15,470 --> 00:50:18,130
So the second
suggested answer is

836
00:50:18,130 --> 00:50:20,870
you can overfit on data
that is not super clean.

837
00:50:20,870 --> 00:50:24,670
And I will go a bit more into
detail on what that means.

838
00:50:24,670 --> 00:50:25,170
Yeah.

839
00:50:25,170 --> 00:50:26,070
You wanted to add?

840
00:50:26,070 --> 00:50:30,480
[AUDIO OUT]

841
00:50:31,880 --> 00:50:32,380
Yep.

842
00:50:32,380 --> 00:50:32,800
Yeah.

843
00:50:32,800 --> 00:50:33,300
Exactly.

844
00:50:33,300 --> 00:50:35,180
So I guess your two
points are, I guess,

845
00:50:35,180 --> 00:50:37,880
along the same lines, which is
the reward model can be noisy.

846
00:50:37,880 --> 00:50:40,180
So that's exactly it.

847
00:50:40,180 --> 00:50:46,320
So it's a phenomenon that's
called reward hacking, where

848
00:50:46,320 --> 00:50:51,160
if you are trying to optimize
too much for the rewards,

849
00:50:51,160 --> 00:50:56,200
you're basically assuming
that the reward is exactly

850
00:50:56,200 --> 00:50:58,400
quantifying what you want.

851
00:50:58,400 --> 00:51:00,520
But it may not be the
case, because the reward

852
00:51:00,520 --> 00:51:04,800
model itself is imperfect.

853
00:51:04,800 --> 00:51:07,440
So just to make sure that
everyone gets the point,

854
00:51:07,440 --> 00:51:12,120
I'm going to illustrate
that with an example.

855
00:51:12,120 --> 00:51:17,320
So let's suppose that
I'm giving a lecture.

856
00:51:17,320 --> 00:51:20,960
And my objective
is for the lecture

857
00:51:20,960 --> 00:51:22,870
to be as informative
as possible.

858
00:51:25,430 --> 00:51:28,990
So I can take the
choice to have something

859
00:51:28,990 --> 00:51:33,110
that I can quantify to know if
what I'm saying is informative.

860
00:51:33,110 --> 00:51:38,870
So let's suppose if my reward
is how loud the claps are

861
00:51:38,870 --> 00:51:44,710
at the end of the lecture, if
the clapping is a lot or not.

862
00:51:44,710 --> 00:51:50,350
The problem is if I optimize too
much for the volume of clapping

863
00:51:50,350 --> 00:51:56,470
at the end, it may be the
case that if I found out

864
00:51:56,470 --> 00:52:00,950
that you all like jokes
and I start making jokes

865
00:52:00,950 --> 00:52:05,110
and then you clap at the
end, my reward is maximized.

866
00:52:05,110 --> 00:52:06,770
But my objective
is not fulfilled,

867
00:52:06,770 --> 00:52:10,550
which is make the
lecture informative.

868
00:52:10,550 --> 00:52:15,470
So in practice, this
reward hacking phenomenon

869
00:52:15,470 --> 00:52:17,630
is something that
leads your model

870
00:52:17,630 --> 00:52:23,980
to optimize too much on a metric
or a score that is imperfect.

871
00:52:23,980 --> 00:52:26,100
So it can very well
maximize the rewards

872
00:52:26,100 --> 00:52:28,340
but not fulfill what you want.

873
00:52:28,340 --> 00:52:33,860
And this is exactly what the
idea behind reward hacking is.

874
00:52:33,860 --> 00:52:34,640
So yeah.

875
00:52:34,640 --> 00:52:36,000
And another reason by the way.

876
00:52:36,000 --> 00:52:38,740
So it's one reason is
because your base model

877
00:52:38,740 --> 00:52:39,760
is already great.

878
00:52:39,760 --> 00:52:41,240
It knows a lot of things.

879
00:52:41,240 --> 00:52:44,800
Second one is because the
reward model is imperfect.

880
00:52:44,800 --> 00:52:47,980
So you have this reward
hacking phenomenon.

881
00:52:47,980 --> 00:52:50,660
The third reason is also because
you can have some training

882
00:52:50,660 --> 00:52:53,500
instabilities.

883
00:52:53,500 --> 00:52:55,540
Anyways, we have a
bunch of reasons why we

884
00:52:55,540 --> 00:52:56,930
don't want to deviate too much.

885
00:52:59,460 --> 00:53:03,780
And so in this setup, you
typically have more observations

886
00:53:03,780 --> 00:53:06,700
than in the reward model case.

887
00:53:06,700 --> 00:53:10,300
So you have typically at
least 100K observations.

888
00:53:10,300 --> 00:53:15,020
And the label that you get
here is from the reward model.

889
00:53:15,020 --> 00:53:21,630
And so you start with the model
that you obtained after SFT.

890
00:53:21,630 --> 00:53:23,810
So that's the one
that you trained.

891
00:53:23,810 --> 00:53:28,650
And the loss function
will be something

892
00:53:28,650 --> 00:53:35,490
that will try for you to
maximize the rewards but also

893
00:53:35,490 --> 00:53:39,090
to not have you deviate too
much from the base model.

894
00:53:39,090 --> 00:53:42,050
So we're going to see
exactly how we can do that.

895
00:53:42,050 --> 00:53:45,472
But that's the idea of how our
loss function will look like.

896
00:53:45,472 --> 00:53:46,680
It will have these two parts.

897
00:53:49,850 --> 00:53:52,530
Sounds good?

898
00:53:52,530 --> 00:53:55,290
And as we saw, so
we don't want it

899
00:53:55,290 --> 00:53:58,170
to deviate too much because of
reward hacking and instability

900
00:53:58,170 --> 00:54:01,170
and so on.

901
00:54:01,170 --> 00:54:05,850
So in order to do that, you may
have heard a very popular RL

902
00:54:05,850 --> 00:54:09,490
algorithm that's called PPO.

903
00:54:09,490 --> 00:54:15,290
So PPO stands for proximal
policy optimization.

904
00:54:15,290 --> 00:54:18,250
So the reason why
it's named proximal

905
00:54:18,250 --> 00:54:21,390
is because we do
not want our model

906
00:54:21,390 --> 00:54:24,770
to deviate too much
from the base model.

907
00:54:24,770 --> 00:54:28,230
And we're going to
see how we do that.

908
00:54:28,230 --> 00:54:32,430
So this is roughly how our
loss function will look like.

909
00:54:32,430 --> 00:54:34,710
So we'll have a part
that is a reward

910
00:54:34,710 --> 00:54:37,830
model that we want to maximize.

911
00:54:37,830 --> 00:54:41,990
And then some other
part that is around

912
00:54:41,990 --> 00:54:47,230
measuring how far the
distribution of the policy

913
00:54:47,230 --> 00:54:52,230
that we're training is to the
reference model or the base

914
00:54:52,230 --> 00:54:52,730
model.

915
00:54:52,730 --> 00:54:56,980
So here, the reference model
would be your SFT model.

916
00:55:00,590 --> 00:55:04,030
So you have these two parts.

917
00:55:04,030 --> 00:55:08,790
Does the formulation of the
loss roughly make sense so far?

918
00:55:08,790 --> 00:55:09,610
That makes sense?

919
00:55:12,830 --> 00:55:13,670
Cool.

920
00:55:13,670 --> 00:55:14,590
OK.

921
00:55:14,590 --> 00:55:16,750
KL divergence.

922
00:55:16,750 --> 00:55:18,680
So I'm just talking
about KL divergence,

923
00:55:18,680 --> 00:55:22,780
but I don't want to just
assume you know what that is.

924
00:55:22,780 --> 00:55:29,140
So the KL divergence
is some measure.

925
00:55:29,140 --> 00:55:31,660
I don't want to say distance
because distance has

926
00:55:31,660 --> 00:55:33,120
a lot of connotations to it.

927
00:55:33,120 --> 00:55:36,620
It's not a distance,
but it's some measure

928
00:55:36,620 --> 00:55:42,500
of how far two probability
distributions are.

929
00:55:42,500 --> 00:55:45,420
So you take a probability
distribution, let's say, P

930
00:55:45,420 --> 00:55:47,620
and another one
probability distribution

931
00:55:47,620 --> 00:55:51,940
Q. And you compute
this formula, which

932
00:55:51,940 --> 00:55:55,660
is the sum of p i
log of p i over q i.

933
00:55:55,660 --> 00:55:58,620
Just gives you a
number of how distant

934
00:55:58,620 --> 00:56:05,500
or how far these two
probability distributions are.

935
00:56:05,500 --> 00:56:10,900
So you want to
minimize the loss.

936
00:56:10,900 --> 00:56:14,760
So I guess you want to
minimize how far they are.

937
00:56:19,130 --> 00:56:22,530
Does that make sense
that we're using this?

938
00:56:22,530 --> 00:56:24,410
Yeah.

939
00:56:24,410 --> 00:56:24,910
OK.

940
00:56:24,910 --> 00:56:27,590
So just one little question.

941
00:56:27,590 --> 00:56:29,010
So OK.

942
00:56:29,010 --> 00:56:34,490
Is the KL divergence positive or
negative or what can you tell me

943
00:56:34,490 --> 00:56:35,870
about the KL divergence?

944
00:56:40,090 --> 00:56:42,090
Have you seen the-- yeah.

945
00:56:42,090 --> 00:56:42,768
It's positive.

946
00:56:42,768 --> 00:56:43,560
Why is it positive?

947
00:56:43,560 --> 00:56:47,270
[AUDIO OUT]

948
00:56:54,790 --> 00:56:55,290
Yeah.

949
00:56:55,290 --> 00:56:55,910
But why?

950
00:56:59,530 --> 00:57:02,190
So maybe we can come
later but great, great.

951
00:57:02,190 --> 00:57:05,070
I think the result is here,
but I guess I want to why.

952
00:57:05,070 --> 00:57:07,770
Yes.

953
00:57:07,770 --> 00:57:08,330
Exactly.

954
00:57:08,330 --> 00:57:10,750
So yeah, if you use
Jensen's inequality--

955
00:57:10,750 --> 00:57:13,590
because when you look
at this formula, I mean,

956
00:57:13,590 --> 00:57:16,100
luck can take positive
and negative values,

957
00:57:16,100 --> 00:57:17,440
it's not super clear.

958
00:57:17,440 --> 00:57:20,400
But yeah, the way you
prove that it's always

959
00:57:20,400 --> 00:57:24,960
positive or equal to 0 is
with the Jensen's inequality.

960
00:57:24,960 --> 00:57:28,840
And so yes, this
quantity is equal to 0

961
00:57:28,840 --> 00:57:31,620
if and only if P
and Q are equal.

962
00:57:34,520 --> 00:57:36,850
Cool.

963
00:57:36,850 --> 00:57:41,600
So with that, we're going to
go a little bit more in depth

964
00:57:41,600 --> 00:57:46,160
into the loss function.

965
00:57:46,160 --> 00:57:48,360
So I mentioned that
the loss function

966
00:57:48,360 --> 00:57:54,280
tries to maximize for
rewards but also make it

967
00:57:54,280 --> 00:57:58,920
so that the model does not
deviate too much from the base

968
00:57:58,920 --> 00:58:00,600
model.

969
00:58:00,600 --> 00:58:04,383
Well, there is
something that I've

970
00:58:04,383 --> 00:58:05,800
lied a little bit
about too, which

971
00:58:05,800 --> 00:58:09,160
is we don't want to
maximize rewards.

972
00:58:09,160 --> 00:58:13,950
We actually want to maximize
a quantity called advantage.

973
00:58:13,950 --> 00:58:15,830
So what is the advantage?

974
00:58:15,830 --> 00:58:18,150
So you can think
of the advantage

975
00:58:18,150 --> 00:58:25,078
as being how much better
is your output compared

976
00:58:25,078 --> 00:58:26,120
to what you would expect.

977
00:58:29,070 --> 00:58:32,870
So people typically
use advantage

978
00:58:32,870 --> 00:58:37,130
to make the whole process
be, I guess, more stable,

979
00:58:37,130 --> 00:58:40,230
the training more stable.

980
00:58:40,230 --> 00:58:45,350
And we estimate that
advantage with a function

981
00:58:45,350 --> 00:58:48,010
called a value function, which
we will see in a little bit.

982
00:58:48,010 --> 00:58:49,390
Did you have a question?

983
00:58:49,390 --> 00:58:50,470
No, no question.

984
00:58:50,470 --> 00:58:52,790
So we have two quantities.

985
00:58:52,790 --> 00:58:53,290
Right.

986
00:58:53,290 --> 00:58:58,450
We have the reward that we
saw previously how to compute,

987
00:58:58,450 --> 00:59:05,790
which is given a prompt, given
a completion, how good is

988
00:59:05,790 --> 00:59:08,710
this prompt and completion?

989
00:59:08,710 --> 00:59:13,340
And then the value function
is another estimation,

990
00:59:13,340 --> 00:59:16,860
but this estimation is not
at the completion level.

991
00:59:16,860 --> 00:59:20,340
It is actually at
the token level.

992
00:59:20,340 --> 00:59:25,620
So what we're doing here is
we're taking the prompt along

993
00:59:25,620 --> 00:59:31,140
with the partial
generation as input.

994
00:59:31,140 --> 00:59:35,060
And we're trying to estimate
what the reward would

995
00:59:35,060 --> 00:59:41,700
be if we were to continue to
generate the output following

996
00:59:41,700 --> 00:59:42,250
the policy.

997
00:59:45,300 --> 00:59:48,100
So I'm just going to repeat
this one more time because it's

998
00:59:48,100 --> 00:59:49,820
charged in meaning.

999
00:59:49,820 --> 00:59:55,020
The value function is a
token level estimation

1000
00:59:55,020 --> 01:00:00,260
of the reward that
takes in a partial input

1001
01:00:00,260 --> 01:00:03,860
and predicts the reward.

1002
01:00:03,860 --> 01:00:08,060
So that predicts
the reward if you

1003
01:00:08,060 --> 01:00:12,050
were to follow the policy
in your generation.

1004
01:00:12,050 --> 01:00:15,130
So this value
function is something

1005
01:00:15,130 --> 01:00:17,730
you will see in
papers as something

1006
01:00:17,730 --> 01:00:21,610
that people have to
train when they do PPO.

1007
01:00:21,610 --> 01:00:24,610
And it's typically
because people

1008
01:00:24,610 --> 01:00:28,970
need to have this value function
when they compute the advantage

1009
01:00:28,970 --> 01:00:31,090
that I mentioned above.

1010
01:00:31,090 --> 01:00:38,210
And this value function is
typically trained jointly

1011
01:00:38,210 --> 01:00:40,450
with the policy.

1012
01:00:40,450 --> 01:00:44,650
So in other terms,
you have your LLM,

1013
01:00:44,650 --> 01:00:49,210
which is initialized
as the SFT model, which

1014
01:00:49,210 --> 01:00:51,490
generates the prediction.

1015
01:00:51,490 --> 01:01:03,230
So what you typically do is also
have some value head that also--

1016
01:01:03,230 --> 01:01:05,230
so this time, it's not a
classification problem.

1017
01:01:05,230 --> 01:01:07,040
It's a regression problem.

1018
01:01:07,040 --> 01:01:11,080
You try to estimate
the final reward

1019
01:01:11,080 --> 01:01:16,240
if you were to continue to
generate according to policy.

1020
01:01:16,240 --> 01:01:18,320
So this is typically
something that you also

1021
01:01:18,320 --> 01:01:22,760
need to train jointly
with the policy.

1022
01:01:22,760 --> 01:01:26,520
And I am intentionally
not going too much

1023
01:01:26,520 --> 01:01:30,840
into detail as to exactly how
that advantage is formulated.

1024
01:01:30,840 --> 01:01:33,560
It is just beyond the
scope of this class.

1025
01:01:33,560 --> 01:01:36,240
But in case you're
interested, I would highly

1026
01:01:36,240 --> 01:01:40,240
recommend reading this paper,
which is mathematically

1027
01:01:40,240 --> 01:01:44,680
involved about the generalized
advantage estimation

1028
01:01:44,680 --> 01:01:48,520
methods, which people
typically use for this.

1029
01:01:48,520 --> 01:01:51,160
So it's this high dimensional
continuous control

1030
01:01:51,160 --> 01:01:54,560
using generalized
advantage estimation paper.

1031
01:01:54,560 --> 01:01:57,480
So if you're interested, just
feel free to take a look.

1032
01:01:57,480 --> 01:02:02,080
But this is typically the
method that people use

1033
01:02:02,080 --> 01:02:06,430
to estimate these advantages.

1034
01:02:06,430 --> 01:02:08,790
So now, we're going
to see in a second

1035
01:02:08,790 --> 01:02:11,030
where those advantages are used.

1036
01:02:11,030 --> 01:02:13,910
But just as a high level,
does that make sense

1037
01:02:13,910 --> 01:02:16,970
to everyone what we're
trying to achieve here?

1038
01:02:16,970 --> 01:02:20,610
[AUDIO OUT]

1039
01:02:21,110 --> 01:02:22,656
Yeah.

1040
01:02:22,656 --> 01:02:29,390
So in other words, what we
want is to maximize the rewards

1041
01:02:29,390 --> 01:02:32,470
but not deviate too much
from the base model.

1042
01:02:32,470 --> 01:02:36,550
But what we want
is to actually find

1043
01:02:36,550 --> 01:02:42,790
a way to make the rewards a
bit more relative as to what

1044
01:02:42,790 --> 01:02:45,390
you would actually expect.

1045
01:02:45,390 --> 01:02:47,270
So you want to
compare the rewards

1046
01:02:47,270 --> 01:02:53,090
that you're obtaining with an
average response if you want.

1047
01:02:53,090 --> 01:02:55,750
The idea is, OK,
if you are having

1048
01:02:55,750 --> 01:02:59,450
a great reward, what would be
the reward in the average case?

1049
01:02:59,450 --> 01:03:02,870
And you want to maximize that.

1050
01:03:02,870 --> 01:03:08,900
And the reason why people use
these reward minus baseline

1051
01:03:08,900 --> 01:03:13,820
is because it reduces the
variance of these estimates,

1052
01:03:13,820 --> 01:03:19,060
and it just makes the training
just go faster typically.

1053
01:03:19,060 --> 01:03:22,460
So that's why people
use that part.

1054
01:03:22,460 --> 01:03:27,180
But in order to compute the
advantage, what people use

1055
01:03:27,180 --> 01:03:31,660
is a method called generalized
advantage estimation, which

1056
01:03:31,660 --> 01:03:35,140
you can think of
it as a big formula

1057
01:03:35,140 --> 01:03:40,540
with some hyper-parameters
that is in the paper below.

1058
01:03:40,540 --> 01:03:41,590
That's the general idea.

1059
01:03:44,900 --> 01:03:45,500
Cool.

1060
01:03:45,500 --> 01:03:46,800
OK.

1061
01:03:46,800 --> 01:03:48,300
Looking at the
time, so we're going

1062
01:03:48,300 --> 01:03:54,140
to look at two typical
variants of the PPO loss.

1063
01:03:54,140 --> 01:03:58,700
The first one is
called PPO-Clip.

1064
01:03:58,700 --> 01:04:05,490
So the idea here is to prevent
the updates to our model

1065
01:04:05,490 --> 01:04:11,210
from being too large from
one iteration to the next.

1066
01:04:11,210 --> 01:04:16,090
So what you have is this
loss formulation, which

1067
01:04:16,090 --> 01:04:23,410
is the minimum of the ratio, and
we're going to see what that is,

1068
01:04:23,410 --> 01:04:26,970
times the advantage
and some clipping

1069
01:04:26,970 --> 01:04:31,010
of that ratio between
two bands, which

1070
01:04:31,010 --> 01:04:35,330
we're going to see in a
second, times that advantage.

1071
01:04:35,330 --> 01:04:38,050
So before we go
into details, I just

1072
01:04:38,050 --> 01:04:40,170
want to call out
a few things that

1073
01:04:40,170 --> 01:04:45,970
may seem like it's confusing
because it was confusing to me.

1074
01:04:45,970 --> 01:04:51,930
So first of all, that formula
is expressed as L is equal to,

1075
01:04:51,930 --> 01:04:55,510
but it's actually not
something we want to minimize,

1076
01:04:55,510 --> 01:04:58,130
something that we
want to maximize.

1077
01:04:58,130 --> 01:05:02,880
So what people typically
mean by L is loss.

1078
01:05:02,880 --> 01:05:05,420
So yeah, just know that
we want to maximize that.

1079
01:05:05,420 --> 01:05:08,480
We don't want to minimize.

1080
01:05:08,480 --> 01:05:10,800
The second thing is
we're introducing

1081
01:05:10,800 --> 01:05:14,080
a term called R of theta.

1082
01:05:14,080 --> 01:05:17,160
This is not the reward model.

1083
01:05:17,160 --> 01:05:21,140
So typically, people
use R to say the reward.

1084
01:05:21,140 --> 01:05:23,520
But here, it's not the reward.

1085
01:05:23,520 --> 01:05:30,520
It's actually the ratio in the
probabilities between our policy

1086
01:05:30,520 --> 01:05:34,280
and the policy from the
previous step, which is

1087
01:05:34,280 --> 01:05:38,960
denoted pi old, pi theta old.

1088
01:05:38,960 --> 01:05:45,000
So it quantifies how different
your policy at the current stage

1089
01:05:45,000 --> 01:05:48,960
is to your old policy.

1090
01:05:48,960 --> 01:05:54,860
So here, when we say, old,
it's not the SFT model.

1091
01:05:54,860 --> 01:05:55,900
It's not the SFT model.

1092
01:05:55,900 --> 01:06:01,510
It's the model at the previous
iteration during the oral stage,

1093
01:06:01,510 --> 01:06:06,030
because here what we want
is for the policy to not

1094
01:06:06,030 --> 01:06:08,220
have updates that are too wide.

1095
01:06:11,990 --> 01:06:12,730
So far, so good?

1096
01:06:12,730 --> 01:06:13,230
Yeah.

1097
01:06:13,230 --> 01:06:16,950
[AUDIO OUT]

1098
01:06:16,950 --> 01:06:18,430
What is A?

1099
01:06:18,430 --> 01:06:20,510
A is our advantage.

1100
01:06:20,510 --> 01:06:23,590
So you can think of it as this
complicated formula that's

1101
01:06:23,590 --> 01:06:26,350
a function of the reward
and the value function

1102
01:06:26,350 --> 01:06:34,430
that just tells you how good
your piece is basically.

1103
01:06:34,430 --> 01:06:39,230
So this complicated
formula, we're

1104
01:06:39,230 --> 01:06:43,270
just going to see
why it makes sense.

1105
01:06:43,270 --> 01:06:50,030
So if the advantage
is positive, it

1106
01:06:50,030 --> 01:06:55,110
means that we somehow
want to reinforce

1107
01:06:55,110 --> 01:06:58,260
whatever was generated.

1108
01:06:58,260 --> 01:07:01,980
And so here, our objective
function will look like this.

1109
01:07:01,980 --> 01:07:07,820
So if A is positive,
then this L of CLIP

1110
01:07:07,820 --> 01:07:13,660
will look some linear
function as a function of R

1111
01:07:13,660 --> 01:07:17,820
because it's R times A.

1112
01:07:17,820 --> 01:07:20,820
So it's a linear function
as a function of R.

1113
01:07:20,820 --> 01:07:28,460
And then after 1 plus
epsilon, it will just be flat.

1114
01:07:28,460 --> 01:07:33,420
So why do we want such
a shape for our graph?

1115
01:07:33,420 --> 01:07:38,900
Well, we need to think
again about what R means.

1116
01:07:38,900 --> 01:07:43,380
So if A is positive,
meaning it's something

1117
01:07:43,380 --> 01:07:46,980
that we want to
reinforce, we typically

1118
01:07:46,980 --> 01:07:54,890
want the probability of whatever
happened to be increased.

1119
01:07:54,890 --> 01:08:03,770
So we want R to be higher, but
we don't want it to be too high.

1120
01:08:03,770 --> 01:08:06,750
So that's why we have
this clipping mechanism.

1121
01:08:10,490 --> 01:08:13,870
So that's why we have
this clipping here.

1122
01:08:13,870 --> 01:08:20,689
We want to, I guess, maximize L.
So we go towards increasing R,

1123
01:08:20,689 --> 01:08:24,569
but we don't want to
increase R too much.

1124
01:08:24,569 --> 01:08:27,850
So that's the
rationale for this.

1125
01:08:27,850 --> 01:08:34,090
But when A is negative, it means
that somehow what we've done

1126
01:08:34,090 --> 01:08:38,090
is something that we
don't want to do as much.

1127
01:08:38,090 --> 01:08:42,410
So in order to maximize
L, what we want

1128
01:08:42,410 --> 01:08:48,569
is to actually decrease the
probability of just generating

1129
01:08:48,569 --> 01:08:50,290
what we generated.

1130
01:08:50,290 --> 01:08:57,200
So we want R to be smaller
because it also increases L,

1131
01:08:57,200 --> 01:08:59,140
but we don't want it
to be much smaller.

1132
01:08:59,140 --> 01:09:02,279
We don't want too big
of an update, which

1133
01:09:02,279 --> 01:09:06,399
is why we have this
clipping mechanism here.

1134
01:09:06,399 --> 01:09:10,960
So in other words, this
super complicated formula

1135
01:09:10,960 --> 01:09:13,359
can be just
intuitively explained

1136
01:09:13,359 --> 01:09:16,200
with what I just
mentioned, which

1137
01:09:16,200 --> 01:09:20,760
is if you have
positive advantages,

1138
01:09:20,760 --> 01:09:25,200
you want to reinforce
the fact of generating

1139
01:09:25,200 --> 01:09:29,359
this output because this is
something that the model likes.

1140
01:09:29,359 --> 01:09:33,800
I mean, by model, I
mean the reward model,

1141
01:09:33,800 --> 01:09:36,120
but you don't want it
to update it too much,

1142
01:09:36,120 --> 01:09:38,160
which is why you
have this clipping.

1143
01:09:38,160 --> 01:09:43,040
And same when the
advantage is less than 0.

1144
01:09:43,040 --> 01:09:48,800
I guess you want to down weight
the probability of this output

1145
01:09:48,800 --> 01:09:49,580
from happening.

1146
01:09:49,580 --> 01:09:51,550
So you want to have
a smaller R, which

1147
01:09:51,550 --> 01:09:54,630
is your ratio between the
policy you're training

1148
01:09:54,630 --> 01:09:56,830
with respect to the old
one, but you don't want

1149
01:09:56,830 --> 01:10:00,030
to be too small
either, again, to not

1150
01:10:00,030 --> 01:10:01,540
make too big of an update.

1151
01:10:04,110 --> 01:10:05,180
Does this make sense?

1152
01:10:09,190 --> 01:10:11,090
Does this roughly make sense?

1153
01:10:11,090 --> 01:10:11,590
OK.

1154
01:10:11,590 --> 01:10:12,590
Roughly makes sense.

1155
01:10:12,590 --> 01:10:13,310
Cool.

1156
01:10:13,310 --> 01:10:19,710
I will just recommend just
rereading this formula,

1157
01:10:19,710 --> 01:10:22,090
just remembering
what I mentioned.

1158
01:10:22,090 --> 01:10:25,910
And hopefully, it will
make a bit more sense.

1159
01:10:25,910 --> 01:10:29,070
But yeah, happy to answer any
questions if there are any.

1160
01:10:29,070 --> 01:10:30,190
Yeah.

1161
01:10:30,190 --> 01:10:31,850
Oh, yeah.

1162
01:10:31,850 --> 01:10:32,350
Yeah.

1163
01:10:32,350 --> 01:10:36,302
[AUDIO OUT]

1164
01:10:43,510 --> 01:10:46,870
So the question is, what
happens where it's not--

1165
01:10:46,870 --> 01:10:48,410
it's the same as ReLU.

1166
01:10:48,410 --> 01:10:51,140
You will basically
use the same methods.

1167
01:10:51,140 --> 01:10:52,640
So yeah, it's the same thing.

1168
01:10:52,640 --> 01:10:53,140
Yeah.

1169
01:10:53,140 --> 01:10:58,260
[AUDIO OUT]

1170
01:10:58,260 --> 01:10:59,563
So great question.

1171
01:10:59,563 --> 01:11:00,980
The question is,
why are you using

1172
01:11:00,980 --> 01:11:03,620
from the previous iteration
and not the base model?

1173
01:11:03,620 --> 01:11:08,060
Because actually, we
don't want just to not

1174
01:11:08,060 --> 01:11:09,880
be too far from the base model.

1175
01:11:09,880 --> 01:11:13,700
We also want our updates
to be not too extreme

1176
01:11:13,700 --> 01:11:16,140
from one iteration to another.

1177
01:11:16,140 --> 01:11:21,420
And this is to improve
with stability of training.

1178
01:11:21,420 --> 01:11:24,570
So this is just like another
additional constraint we want.

1179
01:11:24,570 --> 01:11:28,214
[AUDIO OUT]

1180
01:11:29,403 --> 01:11:31,320
Question is are we
considering the base model?

1181
01:11:31,320 --> 01:11:32,280
We will consider it.

1182
01:11:32,280 --> 01:11:33,720
And I will tell you exactly.

1183
01:11:33,720 --> 01:11:37,080
But in this
formulation, we are not.

1184
01:11:37,080 --> 01:11:38,700
In this formulation, we are not.

1185
01:11:38,700 --> 01:11:40,780
But in the formulation
we're using typically

1186
01:11:40,780 --> 01:11:46,950
for LLM based RL, we
are and we will see how.

1187
01:11:46,950 --> 01:11:47,450
Yeah.

1188
01:11:47,450 --> 01:11:51,450
[AUDIO OUT]

1189
01:12:04,250 --> 01:12:04,850
Yeah.

1190
01:12:04,850 --> 01:12:07,290
So the question is,
how do you quantify R?

1191
01:12:07,290 --> 01:12:07,960
What is R?

1192
01:12:07,960 --> 01:12:08,710
What does it mean?

1193
01:12:08,710 --> 01:12:13,330
So it's typically the
probability of a token happening

1194
01:12:13,330 --> 01:12:14,570
with respect to the inputs.

1195
01:12:14,570 --> 01:12:16,570
So you can think of the
probability distribution

1196
01:12:16,570 --> 01:12:19,550
that you get at the
output of your LLM.

1197
01:12:19,550 --> 01:12:20,510
So you would use that.

1198
01:12:24,010 --> 01:12:25,230
Cool.

1199
01:12:25,230 --> 01:12:29,030
So this is the first variant
that the PPO paper mentions.

1200
01:12:29,030 --> 01:12:30,970
So it's called PPO-Clip.

1201
01:12:33,530 --> 01:12:35,610
So the second
variant that we have

1202
01:12:35,610 --> 01:12:39,410
is the one that uses
KL divergence, which

1203
01:12:39,410 --> 01:12:41,570
is called KL penalty.

1204
01:12:41,570 --> 01:12:46,320
And this one is a
function of the ratio

1205
01:12:46,320 --> 01:12:51,640
times the advantage
minus the KL divergence

1206
01:12:51,640 --> 01:12:56,480
between the old policy, which
is the previous iteration,

1207
01:12:56,480 --> 01:12:59,560
and the current iteration.

1208
01:12:59,560 --> 01:13:03,760
So you had a great point, which
is why are we using the old?

1209
01:13:03,760 --> 01:13:08,080
In fact, old means
previous RL iteration.

1210
01:13:08,080 --> 01:13:12,840
But nowadays, people
use the reference.

1211
01:13:12,840 --> 01:13:14,280
So it's just a change--

1212
01:13:14,280 --> 01:13:18,360
because this paper has
been published in 2017,

1213
01:13:18,360 --> 01:13:24,000
where in 2025, LLMs, they came
more into something that was

1214
01:13:24,000 --> 01:13:25,340
popular in the 2020s.

1215
01:13:25,340 --> 01:13:29,160
So yeah, there's just
been this difference

1216
01:13:29,160 --> 01:13:31,000
in what you put there.

1217
01:13:31,000 --> 01:13:32,760
So yeah, it's
indeed the reference

1218
01:13:32,760 --> 01:13:35,420
that you would typically
put in a KL divergence.

1219
01:13:38,160 --> 01:13:41,160
The other thing
that I will say is

1220
01:13:41,160 --> 01:13:45,230
that nowadays,
when someone wants

1221
01:13:45,230 --> 01:13:50,430
to train a policy using
PPO, they would typically

1222
01:13:50,430 --> 01:13:54,550
use the KL divergence,
and they would also maybe

1223
01:13:54,550 --> 01:14:00,470
mix it with the clipping
thing with the old iteration.

1224
01:14:00,470 --> 01:14:03,630
They will basically mix the two.

1225
01:14:03,630 --> 01:14:05,710
There are many
different formulations

1226
01:14:05,710 --> 01:14:06,970
of what the loss can be.

1227
01:14:06,970 --> 01:14:09,570
So what I'm saying
is not always true.

1228
01:14:09,570 --> 01:14:11,370
But this is what
people sometimes do.

1229
01:14:11,370 --> 01:14:12,570
They sometimes mix the two.

1230
01:14:15,710 --> 01:14:17,410
Cool.

1231
01:14:17,410 --> 01:14:21,070
So I talked to you
about PPO and how

1232
01:14:21,070 --> 01:14:24,290
it allowed you to
maximize rewards,

1233
01:14:24,290 --> 01:14:29,150
maximize advantages by not
making your model deviate

1234
01:14:29,150 --> 01:14:31,870
too much from the
base model and also

1235
01:14:31,870 --> 01:14:35,270
from the previous iteration.

1236
01:14:35,270 --> 01:14:39,990
But the problem is that for
PPO, you need a lot of models.

1237
01:14:39,990 --> 01:14:42,380
So you need your policy,
you need your LLM

1238
01:14:42,380 --> 01:14:44,500
that you're training.

1239
01:14:44,500 --> 01:14:48,820
You also need the value
function, which what I mentioned

1240
01:14:48,820 --> 01:14:53,420
is used for the
advantage estimation.

1241
01:14:53,420 --> 01:14:58,740
You also need the
reward model of course.

1242
01:14:58,740 --> 01:15:00,700
And then you need
the base model.

1243
01:15:00,700 --> 01:15:04,140
So the base model is frozen,
so just the SFT model

1244
01:15:04,140 --> 01:15:07,820
just to be able to compare
with the current policy.

1245
01:15:07,820 --> 01:15:10,580
So it's a lot of models.

1246
01:15:10,580 --> 01:15:12,460
So now, the question
that you may ask

1247
01:15:12,460 --> 01:15:16,500
is, do you really need to have
all these models to perform

1248
01:15:16,500 --> 01:15:18,500
well?

1249
