And the answer is maybe
not, maybe but maybe not.

1250
01:15:24,820 --> 01:15:28,220
And nowadays, there is
a bunch of other methods

1251
01:15:28,220 --> 01:15:31,020
that are becoming more popular.

1252
01:15:31,020 --> 01:15:36,980
So you may have heard in GRPO in
the context of reasoning models.

1253
01:15:36,980 --> 01:15:43,130
So we will look at GRPO in more
detail next week for lecture 6.

1254
01:15:43,130 --> 01:15:46,070
But just know that
there are many variants.

1255
01:15:46,070 --> 01:15:50,990
So PPO is just one algorithm
that has been very popular.

1256
01:15:50,990 --> 01:15:55,050
And even within PPO,
there's been many variants.

1257
01:15:55,050 --> 01:15:59,930
And nowadays, there are
many other RL algorithms

1258
01:15:59,930 --> 01:16:02,970
that are being used.

1259
01:16:02,970 --> 01:16:04,930
Yeah.

1260
01:16:04,930 --> 01:16:10,370
And yeah, if you want to
just anticipate next lecture,

1261
01:16:10,370 --> 01:16:14,690
you can also take a look at this
paper from the Deep Seek team.

1262
01:16:14,690 --> 01:16:17,850
So Deep Seek Math limits
of mathematical reasoning

1263
01:16:17,850 --> 01:16:21,463
in open language models that
introduces the GRPO algorithm.

1264
01:16:21,463 --> 01:16:22,630
But if you don't, it's fine.

1265
01:16:22,630 --> 01:16:27,410
We're going to talk
about it next week.

1266
01:16:27,410 --> 01:16:31,210
So I also want to talk about
some challenges when it

1267
01:16:31,210 --> 01:16:35,530
comes to RL-based approaches.

1268
01:16:35,530 --> 01:16:41,080
So the first one is you need
to have this two-stage process.

1269
01:16:41,080 --> 01:16:44,200
You need to first train
your reward model,

1270
01:16:44,200 --> 01:16:45,880
and then you need
to use the reward

1271
01:16:45,880 --> 01:16:48,920
model to train your policy.

1272
01:16:48,920 --> 01:16:52,840
But the problem is you do
step one, you do step two,

1273
01:16:52,840 --> 01:16:55,920
and then you realize, oh,
wait, step one has a problem.

1274
01:16:55,920 --> 01:16:58,000
Then you need to
redo everything.

1275
01:16:58,000 --> 01:17:02,520
So there is a bunch of
dependencies that can really

1276
01:17:02,520 --> 01:17:04,680
make your life harder.

1277
01:17:04,680 --> 01:17:09,680
And just the training
recipe is not the simplest.

1278
01:17:09,680 --> 01:17:13,080
So that's one downside.

1279
01:17:13,080 --> 01:17:16,480
The second downside is about
the number of hyper-parameters

1280
01:17:16,480 --> 01:17:18,560
that you need to tune.

1281
01:17:18,560 --> 01:17:23,680
So we saw beta from the
KL divergence formulation.

1282
01:17:23,680 --> 01:17:24,920
So that's one.

1283
01:17:24,920 --> 01:17:28,800
We have epsilon from
the PPO-Clip version.

1284
01:17:28,800 --> 01:17:30,280
That's another one.

1285
01:17:30,280 --> 01:17:32,460
The generalized
advantage estimation,

1286
01:17:32,460 --> 01:17:33,940
we have not seen the formula.

1287
01:17:33,940 --> 01:17:36,710
But there's, I think, at
least two hyper-parameters

1288
01:17:36,710 --> 01:17:39,110
that I can think of.

1289
01:17:39,110 --> 01:17:43,110
Anyways, you have
a bunch of them.

1290
01:17:43,110 --> 01:17:45,870
So of course, some
hyper-parameters

1291
01:17:45,870 --> 01:17:47,450
perform better than others.

1292
01:17:47,450 --> 01:17:49,870
And if you need to
retrain, then, well, you

1293
01:17:49,870 --> 01:17:53,230
need to do everything again.

1294
01:17:53,230 --> 01:17:56,610
Then you have some
instability challenges.

1295
01:17:56,610 --> 01:17:59,470
So you can constrain
your iterations

1296
01:17:59,470 --> 01:18:02,650
to not be too wide
to control for that

1297
01:18:02,650 --> 01:18:08,550
but sometimes, it's
not sufficient.

1298
01:18:08,550 --> 01:18:10,190
So in terms of the
metric that you

1299
01:18:10,190 --> 01:18:13,970
can use to monitor
the training, well,

1300
01:18:13,970 --> 01:18:15,380
what is the metric
you would use?

1301
01:18:19,070 --> 01:18:23,090
So we're trying to maximize
rewards in some sense.

1302
01:18:23,090 --> 01:18:24,910
So typically, the
metric that you

1303
01:18:24,910 --> 01:18:27,030
would use to monitor
your training

1304
01:18:27,030 --> 01:18:30,830
would be the average rewards.

1305
01:18:30,830 --> 01:18:32,750
But this is not a great--

1306
01:18:32,750 --> 01:18:37,840
I mean, this is a way to
monitor your training,

1307
01:18:37,840 --> 01:18:41,140
but this is not the
best way necessarily.

1308
01:18:41,140 --> 01:18:44,320
So at least when it came
to pre-training and SFT,

1309
01:18:44,320 --> 01:18:47,500
you had this cross entropy
loss that you were monitoring

1310
01:18:47,500 --> 01:18:51,100
that was really telling
you how your model was

1311
01:18:51,100 --> 01:18:54,820
able to just reproduce
the behavior you

1312
01:18:54,820 --> 01:18:58,340
were trying to make it outputs.

1313
01:18:58,340 --> 01:19:00,780
But yeah, so this is
another challenge.

1314
01:19:00,780 --> 01:19:05,700
And then the other thing
is in the RL world,

1315
01:19:05,700 --> 01:19:11,473
in order for you to know which
completion you should not do

1316
01:19:11,473 --> 01:19:13,140
and which completion
you should do more,

1317
01:19:13,140 --> 01:19:18,660
you need to have some diversity
whenever you generate.

1318
01:19:18,660 --> 01:19:21,460
So if during the RL
training loop, every time

1319
01:19:21,460 --> 01:19:24,740
you have a prompt, you
generate something,

1320
01:19:24,740 --> 01:19:27,740
and then you retry, and you
generate something else that's

1321
01:19:27,740 --> 01:19:31,660
too close, well, it's not
great because you're not

1322
01:19:31,660 --> 01:19:34,930
exploring the set of
possible completions.

1323
01:19:34,930 --> 01:19:36,650
So this is another
challenge you need

1324
01:19:36,650 --> 01:19:39,570
to have in mind, which is
you need to force your model

1325
01:19:39,570 --> 01:19:45,970
to do some exploration to see,
I guess, what can be good.

1326
01:19:45,970 --> 01:19:49,490
And then the last point
is, I mean, a lot of you

1327
01:19:49,490 --> 01:19:51,590
were not familiar with RL.

1328
01:19:51,590 --> 01:19:55,570
I was not, and it's
not super clear

1329
01:19:55,570 --> 01:19:59,260
why we would necessarily
need RL to do this stage.

1330
01:20:03,050 --> 01:20:05,170
Also, I will say one thing.

1331
01:20:05,170 --> 01:20:10,130
So this RL-based training,
you will hear a lot the term

1332
01:20:10,130 --> 01:20:12,450
on policy training.

1333
01:20:12,450 --> 01:20:15,530
I just want to tell
you what that means.

1334
01:20:15,530 --> 01:20:22,330
So what is different between
this and SFT is during SFT,

1335
01:20:22,330 --> 01:20:27,330
we had some prompts
and some response

1336
01:20:27,330 --> 01:20:32,840
that we wanted our model
to generate, to mimic.

1337
01:20:32,840 --> 01:20:37,720
But here, what we're doing
is at each iteration,

1338
01:20:37,720 --> 01:20:41,600
we're asking our model
to generate an output,

1339
01:20:41,600 --> 01:20:43,880
and then we're using
how good that output is

1340
01:20:43,880 --> 01:20:46,200
to update our model.

1341
01:20:46,200 --> 01:20:48,960
So there is a core
difference between the two,

1342
01:20:48,960 --> 01:20:51,040
because in here,
what we're doing

1343
01:20:51,040 --> 01:20:56,000
is we're asking the model
to generate something,

1344
01:20:56,000 --> 01:20:59,720
whereas for SFT,
we're just using

1345
01:20:59,720 --> 01:21:03,600
some data that is not
necessarily generated

1346
01:21:03,600 --> 01:21:06,000
by our model.

1347
01:21:06,000 --> 01:21:09,720
So on policy training
refers to training

1348
01:21:09,720 --> 01:21:12,720
that involves the
model generating

1349
01:21:12,720 --> 01:21:17,840
from its current policy
and optimizing on that.

1350
01:21:17,840 --> 01:21:22,080
And this is in contrast
with off policy training,

1351
01:21:22,080 --> 01:21:28,145
which is relying on generations
that are not done by the model

1352
01:21:28,145 --> 01:21:29,020
that you're training.

1353
01:21:31,710 --> 01:21:34,990
Does this make sense?

1354
01:21:34,990 --> 01:21:35,910
Yeah.

1355
01:21:35,910 --> 01:21:38,030
So this is a term you
will see a lot, which

1356
01:21:38,030 --> 01:21:40,230
is why I'm telling you.

1357
01:21:40,230 --> 01:21:46,210
And yeah, so PPO is an
on policy algorithm.

1358
01:21:46,210 --> 01:21:46,710
Yeah.

1359
01:21:46,710 --> 01:21:50,686
[AUDIO OUT]

1360
01:21:53,670 --> 01:21:56,810
So the question is, why don't we
do SFT on this preference data?

1361
01:21:56,810 --> 01:22:01,110
Well, SFT, you
tell the model, you

1362
01:22:01,110 --> 01:22:02,870
should generate this
given this input,

1363
01:22:02,870 --> 01:22:05,270
then you should generate
this given this input.

1364
01:22:05,270 --> 01:22:11,190
But you're not telling it about
things you should not generate.

1365
01:22:11,190 --> 01:22:14,870
Let's suppose you have something
that you don't want to happen,

1366
01:22:14,870 --> 01:22:19,030
unless you rewrite that
into perfect sentence,

1367
01:22:19,030 --> 01:22:22,550
there is no way for you in
the traditional SFT framework

1368
01:22:22,550 --> 01:22:27,380
to tell your model
to not generate that.

1369
01:22:27,380 --> 01:22:29,140
But that being said,
it's a great prompt

1370
01:22:29,140 --> 01:22:31,620
because later on in,
let's say, 10 minutes, we

1371
01:22:31,620 --> 01:22:37,420
will see a supervised way of
doing what we did with RL.

1372
01:22:37,420 --> 01:22:40,740
But yeah, it will be
in about 10 minutes.

1373
01:22:40,740 --> 01:22:45,260
But apart from that, does
that roughly make sense?

1374
01:22:45,260 --> 01:22:46,860
Yeah.

1375
01:22:46,860 --> 01:22:47,400
Perfect.

1376
01:22:47,400 --> 01:22:49,940
So in the next few
minutes, we will

1377
01:22:49,940 --> 01:22:55,740
see a method that is actually
used more often than not.

1378
01:22:55,740 --> 01:23:00,380
And this is for people
who have a reward model

1379
01:23:00,380 --> 01:23:03,660
but that don't want to do RL.

1380
01:23:03,660 --> 01:23:05,200
So why do you not want to do RL?

1381
01:23:05,200 --> 01:23:06,720
Because it's expensive.

1382
01:23:06,720 --> 01:23:07,915
You need a lot of models.

1383
01:23:07,915 --> 01:23:09,540
So to your point,
it's indeed expensive

1384
01:23:09,540 --> 01:23:11,940
because you need
all these models.

1385
01:23:11,940 --> 01:23:16,920
And sometimes it's just too
hard to tune that training.

1386
01:23:16,920 --> 01:23:24,220
So you have these methods
called best of N or BoN.

1387
01:23:24,220 --> 01:23:28,170
And the idea here is to
leverage the reward model

1388
01:23:28,170 --> 01:23:32,650
that you obtained in order
to choose the output that you

1389
01:23:32,650 --> 01:23:36,250
will return to the user.

1390
01:23:36,250 --> 01:23:41,770
So the idea here is
you have a prompt,

1391
01:23:41,770 --> 01:23:45,130
and you tell your models,
OK, you actually want

1392
01:23:45,130 --> 01:23:48,190
to have several generations.

1393
01:23:48,190 --> 01:23:51,650
So you generate, let's
say, 4 times, 5 times.

1394
01:23:51,650 --> 01:23:59,570
And what you do is you give a
score to each prompt completion,

1395
01:23:59,570 --> 01:24:02,350
and you just return
the best one,

1396
01:24:02,350 --> 01:24:07,130
the top rated one, which is
why it's called best of N.

1397
01:24:07,130 --> 01:24:09,090
So you have N completions.

1398
01:24:09,090 --> 01:24:15,010
You rate all of them, and
you just return the best one.

1399
01:24:15,010 --> 01:24:16,670
So you have your prompt.

1400
01:24:16,670 --> 01:24:19,850
So our favorite example,
suggest a new activity

1401
01:24:19,850 --> 01:24:21,890
I could do with my teddy bear.

1402
01:24:21,890 --> 01:24:24,260
You put it into your SFT model.

1403
01:24:24,260 --> 01:24:26,300
So you're not training
your SFT model.

1404
01:24:26,300 --> 01:24:28,640
It's as is.

1405
01:24:28,640 --> 01:24:30,800
And you're just
generating, let's suppose,

1406
01:24:30,800 --> 01:24:32,800
three completions.

1407
01:24:32,800 --> 01:24:34,620
The first one is a great answer.

1408
01:24:34,620 --> 01:24:37,000
The second one is
no, don't spend time

1409
01:24:37,000 --> 01:24:39,360
with the teddy bear, which
is not a good answer.

1410
01:24:39,360 --> 01:24:41,820
And then the third one, I
think, is also a good one,

1411
01:24:41,820 --> 01:24:44,200
take your teddy
bear to a picnic.

1412
01:24:44,200 --> 01:24:47,360
You put all of these
into your reward model.

1413
01:24:47,360 --> 01:24:50,380
And this is where I
wanted to respond to you,

1414
01:24:50,380 --> 01:24:52,460
what is an output
of the reward model?

1415
01:24:52,460 --> 01:24:54,400
So it would be a
score like this.

1416
01:24:54,400 --> 01:24:57,760
So for instance, the first
one would be a pretty good

1417
01:24:57,760 --> 01:24:59,443
completion, so it's 0.8.

1418
01:24:59,443 --> 01:25:00,860
The second one is
not good at all.

1419
01:25:00,860 --> 01:25:02,200
Let's say, minus 2.

1420
01:25:02,200 --> 01:25:07,360
And the third one is, let's
say, so-so, so in between.

1421
01:25:07,360 --> 01:25:11,280
So the best of N
method would select

1422
01:25:11,280 --> 01:25:15,720
the top rated one,
which is the first one,

1423
01:25:15,720 --> 01:25:18,670
and this is the one
that you would return.

1424
01:25:22,990 --> 01:25:26,400
So what is one problem
with this approach?

1425
01:25:26,400 --> 01:25:30,418
[AUDIO OUT]

1426
01:25:31,350 --> 01:25:36,430
So the answer is if the model is
bad, then it's going to be bad.

1427
01:25:36,430 --> 01:25:37,550
That's fair.

1428
01:25:37,550 --> 01:25:41,490
But I guess if you make enough
completions with, let's say,

1429
01:25:41,490 --> 01:25:46,030
a high enough temperature,
you will have some diversity.

1430
01:25:46,030 --> 01:25:49,370
So it's a fair point,
which can be a problem,

1431
01:25:49,370 --> 01:25:51,330
but let's suppose
it's indeed a problem.

1432
01:25:51,330 --> 01:25:52,705
Let's suppose it's
not a problem.

1433
01:25:52,705 --> 01:25:54,650
What is another problem
that you may have?

1434
01:25:57,290 --> 01:25:57,790
Yep.

1435
01:25:57,790 --> 01:26:00,550
[AUDIO OUT]

1436
01:26:00,550 --> 01:26:01,590
Yes.

1437
01:26:01,590 --> 01:26:04,850
Yes So the answer is you
query the model many times,

1438
01:26:04,850 --> 01:26:06,330
which is indeed the problem.

1439
01:26:06,330 --> 01:26:08,470
So you're at inference.

1440
01:26:08,470 --> 01:26:11,950
What you want is to not spend
a bunch of money and compute.

1441
01:26:11,950 --> 01:26:14,710
But here, what you're
doing is complete

1442
01:26:14,710 --> 01:26:18,110
your prompt multiple times.

1443
01:26:18,110 --> 01:26:21,320
And this is indeed the
main challenge with this.

1444
01:26:21,320 --> 01:26:26,060
So you indeed skip
the RL training,

1445
01:26:26,060 --> 01:26:31,100
but you're basically pushing
all the work to your inference,

1446
01:26:31,100 --> 01:26:33,220
to the inference stage.

1447
01:26:33,220 --> 01:26:36,780
And this is just making
everything so super costly.

1448
01:26:36,780 --> 01:26:38,920
So when can it be bad?

1449
01:26:38,920 --> 01:26:43,100
So if, for instance,
you're in a case where

1450
01:26:43,100 --> 01:26:47,060
you need to serve your model to,
let's say, a bunch of traffic,

1451
01:26:47,060 --> 01:26:52,480
it may not make sense for you
just from a cost standpoint.

1452
01:26:52,480 --> 01:26:58,740
So I would say, before
taking that route,

1453
01:26:58,740 --> 01:27:01,300
it may be good to
just assess what

1454
01:27:01,300 --> 01:27:04,820
will be your inference traffic,
what would be your training

1455
01:27:04,820 --> 01:27:08,780
cost, and determine
that from there.

1456
01:27:08,780 --> 01:27:12,920
And yeah, I think
that's pretty much it.

1457
01:27:12,920 --> 01:27:16,700
Do we have any
questions on that part?

1458
01:27:16,700 --> 01:27:17,830
Oh, yeah.

1459
01:27:17,830 --> 01:27:18,330
Yeah.

1460
01:27:18,330 --> 01:27:22,210
[AUDIO OUT]

1461
01:27:25,130 --> 01:27:26,538
That sigmoid would be softmax.

1462
01:27:26,538 --> 01:27:27,830
Are you talking about this one?

1463
01:27:31,570 --> 01:27:35,690
So in that algorithm, you're
assuming that your reward

1464
01:27:35,690 --> 01:27:39,130
model is trained.

1465
01:27:39,130 --> 01:27:44,430
So the best of N approach
is you do this training.

1466
01:27:44,430 --> 01:27:48,370
So I guess the sigma here
is pairwise because you

1467
01:27:48,370 --> 01:27:50,400
trained your model in
a pairwise fashion.

1468
01:27:52,930 --> 01:27:57,370
But in the best of
N case, what you do

1469
01:27:57,370 --> 01:28:01,370
is you just use your reward
model to score N times,

1470
01:28:01,370 --> 01:28:04,190
and you just pick
the highest one.

1471
01:28:04,190 --> 01:28:04,690
Yeah.

1472
01:28:04,690 --> 01:28:08,310
[AUDIO OUT]

1473
01:28:33,840 --> 01:28:34,340
Yeah.

1474
01:28:34,340 --> 01:28:37,420
The question is, but what if
all the responses are bad?

1475
01:28:37,420 --> 01:28:41,240
This is definitely
a fair concern.

1476
01:28:41,240 --> 01:28:42,812
And this is indeed a concern.

1477
01:28:42,812 --> 01:28:45,020
So your model needs to be
at least a little bit good.

1478
01:28:47,840 --> 01:28:48,900
Yeah.

1479
01:28:48,900 --> 01:28:49,400
Exactly.

1480
01:28:49,400 --> 01:28:50,880
Yeah.

1481
01:28:50,880 --> 01:28:52,560
Yeah.

1482
01:28:52,560 --> 01:28:53,060
Yeah.

1483
01:28:53,060 --> 01:28:57,020
[AUDIO OUT]

1484
01:29:02,783 --> 01:29:03,700
It's a great question.

1485
01:29:03,700 --> 01:29:05,367
Do you have any
constraint on the scale?

1486
01:29:05,367 --> 01:29:08,600
Well, depending on how
your scaling is done,

1487
01:29:08,600 --> 01:29:11,120
you actually don't
care about the scale

1488
01:29:11,120 --> 01:29:14,750
as long as you take the best
one, the highest one on.

1489
01:29:14,750 --> 01:29:17,630
If you think about it, let's
suppose if you scale it,

1490
01:29:17,630 --> 01:29:20,310
let's say, with a normal
score, the highest one

1491
01:29:20,310 --> 01:29:22,123
will still stay the highest one.

1492
01:29:22,123 --> 01:29:24,540
So in this case, you actually
do not care about the scale.

1493
01:29:24,540 --> 01:29:29,330
[AUDIO OUT]

1494
01:29:29,330 --> 01:29:29,830
Yes.

1495
01:29:29,830 --> 01:29:31,630
You also don't care about that.

1496
01:29:31,630 --> 01:29:34,910
But typically, the
scaling matters

1497
01:29:34,910 --> 01:29:38,830
when it is coming into play
in a loss function, which

1498
01:29:38,830 --> 01:29:41,510
is the case for RL.

1499
01:29:41,510 --> 01:29:46,030
And so that's where people
use some scaling mechanism.

1500
01:29:46,030 --> 01:29:47,300
That's the part that matters.

1501
01:29:50,030 --> 01:29:51,230
Cool.

1502
01:29:51,230 --> 01:29:54,870
And with that, I'm going
to give it to Shervin.

1503
01:29:54,870 --> 01:29:56,790
Thank you, Afshin.

1504
01:29:56,790 --> 01:30:03,110
So for this last part, we're
going to talk about DPO.

1505
01:30:03,110 --> 01:30:06,210
But I'm not going to tell
you what DPO means just yet.

1506
01:30:06,210 --> 01:30:09,550
We're just going to first
listen to the complaints

1507
01:30:09,550 --> 01:30:15,880
we had in the RL world and then
see what we could do about it

1508
01:30:15,880 --> 01:30:20,020
and then how have
folks remedied it.

1509
01:30:20,020 --> 01:30:22,220
So the first thing
that I'm going

1510
01:30:22,220 --> 01:30:24,900
to repeat from
what Afshin covered

1511
01:30:24,900 --> 01:30:31,060
is that in the RL formulation
of PPO, you have to carry,

1512
01:30:31,060 --> 01:30:34,500
during your loss optimization,
a bunch of model weights.

1513
01:30:34,500 --> 01:30:38,340
So when you look at
this loss function,

1514
01:30:38,340 --> 01:30:41,940
you have, first, the
policy of the current model

1515
01:30:41,940 --> 01:30:45,740
you have to optimize for,
the one of the old model

1516
01:30:45,740 --> 01:30:47,980
or the reference model.

1517
01:30:47,980 --> 01:30:52,220
And then you have your advantage
which hides the reward model,

1518
01:30:52,220 --> 01:30:55,240
as well as the value
function that we discussed.

1519
01:30:55,240 --> 01:30:59,740
So all this four,
which is a lot.

1520
01:30:59,740 --> 01:31:03,940
And the second thing
is that, let's say,

1521
01:31:03,940 --> 01:31:07,240
you go with the
approach of best of N,

1522
01:31:07,240 --> 01:31:10,730
you don't do RL, you just
generate multiple times

1523
01:31:10,730 --> 01:31:12,970
and then pick the
best completion.

1524
01:31:12,970 --> 01:31:19,290
As Afshin mentioned, so you have
this latency and cost issues.

1525
01:31:19,290 --> 01:31:24,170
And just for the
sake of thoughts,

1526
01:31:24,170 --> 01:31:27,450
for a thought experiment, let's
suppose we had infinite money,

1527
01:31:27,450 --> 01:31:30,170
would it be still fine?

1528
01:31:30,170 --> 01:31:34,090
So let's suppose you generate
all of these in parallel.

1529
01:31:34,090 --> 01:31:39,010
So you would still need to
wait for the maximum time

1530
01:31:39,010 --> 01:31:43,650
of the generation of an answer
to give you a resulting answer.

1531
01:31:43,650 --> 01:31:47,090
And then if you look at the
distribution of latency,

1532
01:31:47,090 --> 01:31:51,970
usually it's some shape that is
not centered on a single point.

1533
01:31:51,970 --> 01:31:54,970
And when you look at the
probability distribution

1534
01:31:54,970 --> 01:31:58,570
of the max of, let's
say, N answers,

1535
01:31:58,570 --> 01:32:02,090
it will tend to be
shifted to the right.

1536
01:32:02,090 --> 01:32:04,070
So let's suppose you
have infinite money,

1537
01:32:04,070 --> 01:32:08,650
infinite compute, you still
have to wait more than you

1538
01:32:08,650 --> 01:32:10,110
would have on a single pass.

1539
01:32:12,800 --> 01:32:14,350
Do these concerns make sense?

1540
01:32:16,960 --> 01:32:18,060
And OK.

1541
01:32:18,060 --> 01:32:20,840
So there comes the question
that someone was asking,

1542
01:32:20,840 --> 01:32:24,840
why don't we do
supervision all this time?

1543
01:32:24,840 --> 01:32:29,140
And this is the route that
DPO folks have explored.

1544
01:32:29,140 --> 01:32:34,000
So DPO stands for direct
preference optimization.

1545
01:32:34,000 --> 01:32:38,200
So instead of doing these
expensive two-step process of,

1546
01:32:38,200 --> 01:32:42,520
first, finding some reward
model and then iterating

1547
01:32:42,520 --> 01:32:46,760
on the model's weights, it
optimizes a single loss function

1548
01:32:46,760 --> 01:32:50,400
that directly optimizes
for the model's weight.

1549
01:32:50,400 --> 01:32:55,340
And as you can see, there is
no reward involved anymore,

1550
01:32:55,340 --> 01:32:59,760
so no R. And you have
a way to formulate

1551
01:32:59,760 --> 01:33:03,040
what you care about as a
function of your preference

1552
01:33:03,040 --> 01:33:04,120
pairs.

1553
01:33:04,120 --> 01:33:06,160
So in that loss
function, all you

1554
01:33:06,160 --> 01:33:10,970
have is a bunch of variables
and then the sigmoid functions.

1555
01:33:10,970 --> 01:33:17,150
But within the parentheses, you
have the probability of a given

1556
01:33:17,150 --> 01:33:20,230
completion to happen.

1557
01:33:20,230 --> 01:33:23,430
And you have this
subtraction operation

1558
01:33:23,430 --> 01:33:28,630
that compares the probability
of the winning completion

1559
01:33:28,630 --> 01:33:31,030
to happen versus the losing one.

1560
01:33:31,030 --> 01:33:33,870
So as you can see, it's
a direct expression

1561
01:33:33,870 --> 01:33:39,150
with respect to these preference
pairs, which is pretty nice.

1562
01:33:39,150 --> 01:33:43,470
And if you look at
it a bit closer,

1563
01:33:43,470 --> 01:33:46,510
you will recognize what
afshin just mentioned

1564
01:33:46,510 --> 01:33:50,790
regarding Bradley-Terry
formulation because you

1565
01:33:50,790 --> 01:33:56,590
have these expected value
of log of a sigmoid.

1566
01:33:56,590 --> 01:33:59,270
And then within
that sigmoid, you

1567
01:33:59,270 --> 01:34:02,110
have a difference
of terms, where

1568
01:34:02,110 --> 01:34:05,070
you can recognize the
equivalent of what

1569
01:34:05,070 --> 01:34:06,930
you saw as a reward term.

1570
01:34:10,460 --> 01:34:12,640
So I know it's a
lot to see at once.

1571
01:34:12,640 --> 01:34:16,060
The formula is not super pretty.

1572
01:34:16,060 --> 01:34:19,060
Do you have any questions?

1573
01:34:19,060 --> 01:34:23,500
And then we're going to discuss
in a bit what that beta is

1574
01:34:23,500 --> 01:34:26,640
and also how we obtain this
formula in the first place.

1575
01:34:29,500 --> 01:34:31,980
And one thing I will
mention before going

1576
01:34:31,980 --> 01:34:36,420
to that is that the paper is
titled your language model

1577
01:34:36,420 --> 01:34:39,260
is secretly a reward model.

1578
01:34:39,260 --> 01:34:44,180
And the reason for that is
that the reward placeholder

1579
01:34:44,180 --> 01:34:47,220
that you could identify
from this loss function

1580
01:34:47,220 --> 01:34:51,780
is expressed as a
function of your policy.

1581
01:34:51,780 --> 01:34:54,380
So you don't have
any r's in there.

1582
01:34:54,380 --> 01:34:57,260
But when you express the
equivalent of a reward,

1583
01:34:57,260 --> 01:35:02,420
you find the expression
of your model directly.

1584
01:35:02,420 --> 01:35:07,370
So which is pretty
interesting insights.

1585
01:35:07,370 --> 01:35:07,870
OK.

1586
01:35:07,870 --> 01:35:11,490
So but now, let's think
together about how we got there

1587
01:35:11,490 --> 01:35:14,570
in the first place.

1588
01:35:14,570 --> 01:35:18,850
So you recall from
a few slides ago

1589
01:35:18,850 --> 01:35:21,270
the PPO objective that we had.

1590
01:35:21,270 --> 01:35:27,890
So we wanted to maximize
rewards and minimize

1591
01:35:27,890 --> 01:35:30,690
the distance of the
obtained policy with respect

1592
01:35:30,690 --> 01:35:34,370
to the reference one,
which is this trade-off

1593
01:35:34,370 --> 01:35:39,530
between maximizing rewards
and KL divergence term.

1594
01:35:39,530 --> 01:35:41,610
And then you have
this beta coefficient

1595
01:35:41,610 --> 01:35:47,370
that appears there that
controls how much you

1596
01:35:47,370 --> 01:35:51,730
want to penalize going
further from the base model.

1597
01:35:51,730 --> 01:35:56,250
And what this paper did is
that it wrote down this formula

1598
01:35:56,250 --> 01:36:00,730
and then solves what would
be the optimal solution.

1599
01:36:00,730 --> 01:36:05,360
So it expressed the
optimal policy pi star.

1600
01:36:05,360 --> 01:36:08,100
And when you derive
this expression,

1601
01:36:08,100 --> 01:36:11,360
so you get it as
a function of R.

1602
01:36:11,360 --> 01:36:16,720
So that's another term that
was in the objective function.

1603
01:36:16,720 --> 01:36:22,500
And so all these steps
have no extra assumptions.

1604
01:36:22,500 --> 01:36:26,400
It's just a bunch of
derivations that was done.

1605
01:36:26,400 --> 01:36:31,480
And what you can see
here is this Z term

1606
01:36:31,480 --> 01:36:35,240
that stands for a partition
function and that just

1607
01:36:35,240 --> 01:36:37,120
normalizes things.

1608
01:36:37,120 --> 01:36:38,780
But it's not
something that is new.

1609
01:36:38,780 --> 01:36:44,760
It's a function of the terms
that were already in there.

1610
01:36:44,760 --> 01:36:48,220
So when you rearrange
these terms,

1611
01:36:48,220 --> 01:36:55,560
you can equivalently express r
as a function of this pi star.

1612
01:36:55,560 --> 01:36:59,060
So it's just rearranging terms
between these two expressions.

1613
01:36:59,060 --> 01:37:02,430
Nothing too fancy.

1614
01:37:02,430 --> 01:37:07,830
And then the key part
of what this paper did

1615
01:37:07,830 --> 01:37:12,310
is recognize this
term as some reward

1616
01:37:12,310 --> 01:37:20,070
and then express it as part of
a Bradley-Terry formulation.

1617
01:37:20,070 --> 01:37:25,430
So you remember you had this
probability of a completion,

1618
01:37:25,430 --> 01:37:30,070
of a winning completion being
bigger than a losing completion.

1619
01:37:30,070 --> 01:37:34,650
And you had this sigmoid of the
difference between the two r's.

1620
01:37:34,650 --> 01:37:37,590
So basically, they took
this formulation again,

1621
01:37:37,590 --> 01:37:41,190
and they plugged in the
expression they had obtained

1622
01:37:41,190 --> 01:37:44,710
for the optimal reward,
which we had seen

1623
01:37:44,710 --> 01:37:48,310
was a function of the policy.

1624
01:37:48,310 --> 01:37:50,590
So at the end of it,
you plug in things.

1625
01:37:50,590 --> 01:37:54,350
You have no more
rewards, just a function

1626
01:37:54,350 --> 01:37:55,970
of the other parameters.

1627
01:37:55,970 --> 01:38:02,540
So you have this beta and
only the policy in there.

1628
01:38:02,540 --> 01:38:06,720
And the last step is the same
one as Afshin was mentioning,

1629
01:38:06,720 --> 01:38:09,320
once you have this probability
that you want to maximize,

1630
01:38:09,320 --> 01:38:12,660
you can turn it into
a loss function.

1631
01:38:12,660 --> 01:38:15,740
And this loss function is
what this paper proposes

1632
01:38:15,740 --> 01:38:21,080
to optimize in order
to tune policy weights

1633
01:38:21,080 --> 01:38:24,150
in order to align it with
this preference data.

1634
01:38:26,780 --> 01:38:33,180
So I simplified a lot the
quite heavy steps of this paper

1635
01:38:33,180 --> 01:38:35,820
into these few steps.

1636
01:38:35,820 --> 01:38:36,630
Do they make sense?

1637
01:38:42,980 --> 01:38:46,660
And the beta that we see
here is the same beta

1638
01:38:46,660 --> 01:38:51,620
as we had seen in the PPO
formulation, so typically taken

1639
01:38:51,620 --> 01:38:54,600
around 0.1 if you want
some order of magnitude.

1640
01:38:54,600 --> 01:38:57,210
So beta is a
hyper-parameter, and all

1641
01:38:57,210 --> 01:38:59,430
you want to optimize
for is the policy.

1642
01:38:59,430 --> 01:39:04,530
And then the preference pairs,
you have them as inputs.

1643
01:39:04,530 --> 01:39:07,390
Makes sense?

1644
01:39:07,390 --> 01:39:07,890
OK.

1645
01:39:07,890 --> 01:39:08,470
Great.

1646
01:39:08,470 --> 01:39:10,930
So now, let's compare
what this method

1647
01:39:10,930 --> 01:39:14,290
gives with respect to RLHF.

1648
01:39:14,290 --> 01:39:19,330
So RLHF is this two-stage
training process where you first

1649
01:39:19,330 --> 01:39:24,250
fit a reward function
and then use it in order

1650
01:39:24,250 --> 01:39:28,450
to do the policy update steps.

1651
01:39:28,450 --> 01:39:32,490
So Afshin was mentioning
it, it's quite heavy.

1652
01:39:32,490 --> 01:39:34,190
We were mentioning
it just before,

1653
01:39:34,190 --> 01:39:36,010
you need a lot of
models in memory

1654
01:39:36,010 --> 01:39:39,470
and then training
stability is a concern.

1655
01:39:39,470 --> 01:39:42,150
You don't have
direct supervision.

1656
01:39:42,150 --> 01:39:45,530
You rely on the policy
of the current model

1657
01:39:45,530 --> 01:39:47,650
to generate the next updates.

1658
01:39:47,650 --> 01:39:50,890
So there is a lot
of complexity in it.

1659
01:39:50,890 --> 01:39:53,370
And as opposed to that,
this DPO formulation

1660
01:39:53,370 --> 01:39:58,320
gives a supervised way to think
about preference tuning, where

1661
01:39:58,320 --> 01:40:00,640
you just take this
preference pairs,

1662
01:40:00,640 --> 01:40:04,920
and you directly fit a
loss function on them.

1663
01:40:04,920 --> 01:40:06,780
And yeah.

1664
01:40:06,780 --> 01:40:09,080
And instead of four
models, you just

1665
01:40:09,080 --> 01:40:12,680
need two because you
had this pi of theta

1666
01:40:12,680 --> 01:40:16,360
and then a pi ref, which
was your base SFT model,

1667
01:40:16,360 --> 01:40:21,080
and you don't need any
other model copies.

1668
01:40:21,080 --> 01:40:29,960
So now, you might want to ask
if it's much easier, why is not

1669
01:40:29,960 --> 01:40:32,640
everyone just simply using DPO?

1670
01:40:32,640 --> 01:40:34,560
So it's not as easy.

1671
01:40:34,560 --> 01:40:39,840
In practice, there are some
pros and cons to each method,

1672
01:40:39,840 --> 01:40:42,880
and the paper that
is listed below

1673
01:40:42,880 --> 01:40:48,520
gives a very interesting study
of the bench-marking differences

1674
01:40:48,520 --> 01:40:50,960
and the steps to get there.

1675
01:40:50,960 --> 01:40:54,830
So just to get the main
lines, overall, PPO

1676
01:40:54,830 --> 01:40:58,350
performs better than DPO.

1677
01:40:58,350 --> 01:41:02,350
And one great thing
about DPO, which

1678
01:41:02,350 --> 01:41:05,270
is the supervision,
the direct supervision,

1679
01:41:05,270 --> 01:41:08,990
comes at the cost of sometimes
fitting something that is not

1680
01:41:08,990 --> 01:41:13,470
the exact distribution that the
model has seen as training time.

1681
01:41:13,470 --> 01:41:17,230
So this paper talks
about it a bit.

1682
01:41:17,230 --> 01:41:22,870
If you train via SFT on the
preference related data,

1683
01:41:22,870 --> 01:41:25,310
you could get
better performance.

1684
01:41:25,310 --> 01:41:33,030
But this shift in distribution
is a challenge intrinsic to DPO,

1685
01:41:33,030 --> 01:41:37,350
because one thing that the
DPO method enables you to have

1686
01:41:37,350 --> 01:41:41,230
is just to not worry about
that reward modeling at all

1687
01:41:41,230 --> 01:41:46,350
and just get some preference
data set out there.

1688
01:41:46,350 --> 01:41:51,140
But the issue with doing so is
exactly that distribution shift.

1689
01:41:51,140 --> 01:41:54,620
So you could either
train SFT on it

1690
01:41:54,620 --> 01:41:57,760
or donate it yourself
and then rate it.

1691
01:41:57,760 --> 01:42:02,440
But that is yet another cost
that you would need to pay.

1692
01:42:05,120 --> 01:42:05,620
Great.

1693
01:42:08,140 --> 01:42:10,820
And yep.

1694
01:42:10,820 --> 01:42:11,920
Any questions?

1695
01:42:14,660 --> 01:42:15,160
Yep.

1696
01:42:15,160 --> 01:42:19,128
[AUDIO OUT]

1697
01:42:21,620 --> 01:42:24,220
So the question is you are
optimizing the parameters

1698
01:42:24,220 --> 01:42:26,200
with respect to the base model.

1699
01:42:26,200 --> 01:42:28,080
So yes, but it's
not the base model.

1700
01:42:28,080 --> 01:42:29,120
It's the current one.

1701
01:42:29,120 --> 01:42:32,720
You have a base model that will
stay fixed in the iterations.

1702
01:42:32,720 --> 01:42:34,980
And it occurs in
the loss function.

1703
01:42:34,980 --> 01:42:37,560
And you're indeed
updating parameters.

1704
01:42:37,560 --> 01:42:41,000
And that will be like
the preference tuned one.

1705
01:42:41,000 --> 01:42:41,500
Yeah.

1706
01:42:41,500 --> 01:42:44,300
So you have two weights, two
set of weights, one frozen, one

1707
01:42:44,300 --> 01:42:45,740
that you update.

1708
01:42:45,740 --> 01:42:46,760
Yeah.

1709
01:42:46,760 --> 01:42:47,260
OK.

1710
01:42:47,260 --> 01:42:48,900
Great.

1711
01:42:48,900 --> 01:42:49,760
Any other questions?

1712
01:42:49,760 --> 01:42:53,585
[AUDIO OUT]

1713
01:42:58,730 --> 01:42:59,230
Yes.

1714
01:42:59,230 --> 01:43:01,670
So the question is instead
of the reference model,

1715
01:43:01,670 --> 01:43:04,390
could you use another
model, another large model?

1716
01:43:04,390 --> 01:43:10,290
So I think that's an
interesting point.

1717
01:43:10,290 --> 01:43:14,090
I guess that would be
a different algorithm.

1718
01:43:14,090 --> 01:43:17,370
And you might lose
a bit the meaning

1719
01:43:17,370 --> 01:43:20,410
of what you're trying to do
because this preference tuning

1720
01:43:20,410 --> 01:43:26,330
stage is trying to align your
responses to what you prefer.

1721
01:43:26,330 --> 01:43:28,890
And you want them to
align with respect

1722
01:43:28,890 --> 01:43:30,890
to what you had learned so far.

1723
01:43:30,890 --> 01:43:32,850
So if you start from
a different model,

1724
01:43:32,850 --> 01:43:36,890
and then you preference
tune a different probability

1725
01:43:36,890 --> 01:43:40,330
distribution, you
might be doing things

1726
01:43:40,330 --> 01:43:44,490
that might not make as much
sense from a loss standpoint.

1727
01:43:44,490 --> 01:43:45,970
But I guess the direction--

1728
01:43:45,970 --> 01:43:49,820
I mean, I cannot tell
a blanket answer there.

1729
01:43:49,820 --> 01:43:52,340
Maybe it could give
interesting behavior,

1730
01:43:52,340 --> 01:43:56,280
but my intuition would tell you
that the point of all of this

1731
01:43:56,280 --> 01:44:00,380
is to start from the last
train checkpoint that you had

1732
01:44:00,380 --> 01:44:03,360
and then further preference
tune the distribution

1733
01:44:03,360 --> 01:44:04,460
of your completions.

1734
01:44:12,720 --> 01:44:16,600
So the suggestion was if
you change the reference

1735
01:44:16,600 --> 01:44:19,280
model, that could be
seen as another SFT

1736
01:44:19,280 --> 01:44:20,320
version of your model.

1737
01:44:20,320 --> 01:44:20,820
Yeah.

1738
01:44:20,820 --> 01:44:21,420
I guess so.

1739
01:44:25,100 --> 01:44:26,240
Great.

1740
01:44:26,240 --> 01:44:30,680
And now, my favorite
part of today.

1741
01:44:30,680 --> 01:44:32,920
So do you all remember
the completions

1742
01:44:32,920 --> 01:44:35,480
we had obtained on
our favorite prompts?

1743
01:44:35,480 --> 01:44:38,600
So can I put my teddy
bear in the washer?

1744
01:44:38,600 --> 01:44:40,600
So if you remember
last episode, we

1745
01:44:40,600 --> 01:44:43,520
had said after
instruction tuning,

1746
01:44:43,520 --> 01:44:46,970
the response was, no,
it might get damaged.

1747
01:44:46,970 --> 01:44:49,470
Try hand washing it instead.

1748
01:44:49,470 --> 01:44:52,110
So does anyone
have any complaints

1749
01:44:52,110 --> 01:44:53,140
regarding this answer?

1750
01:44:59,190 --> 01:45:01,390
So I can give a hint.

1751
01:45:01,390 --> 01:45:04,257
Teddy bears, they indeed
should be hand washed.

1752
01:45:04,257 --> 01:45:05,340
So it's factually correct.

1753
01:45:07,982 --> 01:45:09,690
But let's suppose it's
factually correct.

1754
01:45:09,690 --> 01:45:11,605
What else do you not like?

1755
01:45:11,605 --> 01:45:13,480
I mean, could you not
like about this answer?

1756
01:45:21,810 --> 01:45:22,310
Yeah.

1757
01:45:22,310 --> 01:45:26,570
So the suggestion was it's
asking to try it instead.

1758
01:45:26,570 --> 01:45:31,230
And I guess a broader point
is it's a bit too rough.

1759
01:45:31,230 --> 01:45:32,930
It doesn't sound super friendly.

1760
01:45:32,930 --> 01:45:36,670
And then someone who asks this
question might love teddy bears,

1761
01:45:36,670 --> 01:45:41,550
so you might want to tell
them about it in a gentle way.

1762
01:45:41,550 --> 01:45:45,340
And this is exactly what
preference tuning stage

1763
01:45:45,340 --> 01:45:46,080
is about.

1764
01:45:46,080 --> 01:45:48,880
We don't want to
learn new facts.

1765
01:45:48,880 --> 01:45:52,740
We want to focus on existing
distribution of completions

1766
01:45:52,740 --> 01:45:56,820
and align what the model should
return with respect to what

1767
01:45:56,820 --> 01:45:58,700
the human prefers.

1768
01:45:58,700 --> 01:46:03,820
So on this intuition, the
preference tunes answer

1769
01:46:03,820 --> 01:46:06,820
could be a gentler one.

1770
01:46:06,820 --> 01:46:08,220
It's better not to.

1771
01:46:08,220 --> 01:46:10,620
Your teddy bear could get hurt.

1772
01:46:10,620 --> 01:46:14,880
A gentle hand wash is safer, so
it's conveying the same points

1773
01:46:14,880 --> 01:46:20,500
but in a tone that sounds
much better to the ears

1774
01:46:20,500 --> 01:46:24,300
of the person who asks.

1775
01:46:24,300 --> 01:46:24,800
Great.

1776
01:46:24,800 --> 01:46:26,690
Any questions on the DPO part?

1777
